animal.description:
Betty is our resident shy girl! She is overwhelmed by the shelter environment and is looking for a patient family willing to give her time to adjust. Once she has gotten to know you, Betty will be your new best friend (especially if you share treats with her!) Betty enjoys the company of other polite mellow dogs.  She is approximately 1 year old and heartworm negative. When you first meet Betty she is quiet and wary of meeting new people.  But once you spend time with her she warms up and will stay right by your side. Betty is soulful, completely sweet and just beautiful. Betty will sit, come and is very treat motivated so training Betty is easy. When Betty is comfortable she has the most adorable zoomies ever! 
Betty needs a calm household to decompress and to know she will be safe and loved then Betty White can be her true sweet self. Betty does good with calmer dogs. Since Betty needs a calm environment it is best there are no children in the home. 
Betty White is an American Pitbull mix, approx 1 year old and approx 40 pounds of adorable.

animal.description: Ranger's foster family has this to say about him: Ranger is the epitome of a gentle giant. He has been so sweet and gentle with us and our young children. He seems to be really well socialized with people and dogs. He plays nicely with our female dog and was temperament tested with male dogs at the shelter. Ranger is house trained, crate trained, and doesnt do too bad on a leash either (he has long legs and tends to walk at a fast pace but doesnt really pull). So far he has not reacted at all to other dogs, cats or squirrels on walks. Ranger is a super chill, low energy guy most of the time and loves nothing more then napping either in his crate, on the couch, or on a nice dog bed. He doesnt seem to have a preference with toys, he pretty much loves them all, and is always down for a game of fetch with a ball or stick. Ranger would do well as a family dog and would be a fantastic companion for trips to the park and dog park! Ranger A593852 1Y Male 54.6 lbs, Heartworm Negative

animal.description:
**Due to high volume in rescue adoptions Treasured Animal Rescue highly recommends and adoption application be completed - link below.**

Hello everyone! My name is Ziggy and I am a Pomeranian: They call me a PomPom. I am 5 years young. My foster Mom tells me that I am a bit fat and that I definitely need to go on a strick diet because I should weigh 20 lbs. How dare she! I am just pleasantly plump. 

I find myself looking for a forever home because my Mommy went to heaven. She had something called cancer and I stayed next to her until she fell asleep. I miss her terribly and I hope she is happy, young and healthy wherever heaven is. Maybe she also has plenty of food there too since she use to let me nibble every now and then. My foster mom said: No snacks for you Ziggy! you are too fat! 

I am a happy boy. I follow my foster Mom everywhere and like to lay by her feet.  If I’m lucky, I try to hop into her bed.  There is another dog here and she is my girlfriend. Her name is Pepper and I would love to be adopted together with her. I love riding in the car so when I hear the car keys I run and wait by the door. I am potty trained for pee pads but my foster Mom told me that I better get used to going outside. I am a gentleman and I am well behaved and don't really bark too much so I could be happy in a house or an apartment in the city. I also walk very well on leash! I told you I am a gentleman. 

I am looking for my forever home. I promise you I will be by your side for the rest of my life. I will put a smile on your face every day and will warm your heart at night. One little favor though... can you give me a treat to nibble every now and then? 

Love
Ziggy

To adopt Ziggy please complete an adoption application at www.treasuredanimalrescueinc.org 

Due to the large number of applications we can't get back to you so please check our website for your pet of choice adoption status. 
Sorry we cannot adopt out of the state of IL

animal.description:
MEET BELLA!  Bella is a 7-year-old Staffy mix.  She's a sweet and loving dog that just wants a safe place to call home.  Bella has a medical condition called Dry Eye which requires the application of daily eyedrops for the rest of her life.  She also has some skin lesions on her hind legs that are currently healing.  Bella is still a very strong girl, and would not be a good fit with children due to the combination of her strength and poor sight.  She would be a great fit in a home with adults that will take the time to create a safe space for her.  In the right environment, she will be happy and thrive!  She still has several years left to love and be loved.  She is looking for a foster or forever home!

**** If you see a pet posted from us, they are AVAILABLE (we update constantly). Please apply right away as opposed to inquiring about if they are available. You may ask additional questions you need answered if you can't find info in our description!

If you are interested in adopting and think you can provide a great home for this pet, please complete an online application so that we can better assess if this pet is a good match for you and your family. Once that is complete and we've approved your application, we can set up a time for you to meet your potential companion for life! 

ADOPTION APPLICATION: www.vida4animals.org/adoption-application/

For more information on this pet, please see the contact information.

Adopt Responsibly. Thank you for choosing Rescue!

Baby Girl is active, playful, and would need a nice secure yard where she can safely play. She gets along well with other dogs and would be fine with children. BG is leash trained; and she is very well behaved and calm when walking on her leash. This gorgeous girl is ready for a new family and a new life. Come meet our Baby Girl beauty queen soon and see if she wouldn't be a nice fit for your family.Dog/puppy adoption fees are $120 and cat/kitten adoption fees are $50. However, she is still a very beautiful dog with a sweet demeanor. She is being fostered by someone who has dogs, cats, and kids, and she does well with them all. She is housebroken. This girl is NOT large. She is more of a Boxer size. She doesn't bite or chew things. She's a good girl. Doesn't jump on you but gets excited at times... but that's normal. :)
She will make a great companion for the right person(s).

She just wants love and we are glad that we are able to help get her to a home that will provide the love that she deserves!

animal.description:
The Courtesy Post below means we are offering our website as an additional outlet to help an owner find their dog a new home.  We are not a shelter, it doesn't mean we've met or evaluated the dog, it means we are trying to help this owner find a good, responsible and most of all a loving home.

The below statements were written by the owner:

I have a 5 year old German Shepherd named Tank. 

His birthday is April 7th, 2015. He weighs 90 lbs. 

Unfortunately, my living situation is going to be changing soon in which Tank will need rehomed. 

Tank has all of his shots and is up to date on all of them. He is not neutered though. (Tank will go out on a neuter contract and will be neutered)

He doesn’t know how to interact with other dogs or cats as he’s always been a single dog in his home. 

He’s great with kids and adults, but he has a tendency to be rather vocal and may jump a bit out of excitement.  He knows his basic commands and is potty trained. He’d make a great pet for someone who loves to play fetch as that’s his favorite pastime. He’s super energetic and loyal. 

He was crate trained, however doesn’t like to be in one. He’s left loose in the house when we’re not home and he’s not destructive at all. 
 
He doesn’t walk well at all on a leash, but would love to go for walks. If someone has the patience to train him to walk on a leash, he’d love it. He loves car rides, however paces back and forth and doesn’t sit still.

If you would like to adopt this dog please fill out the adoption application: https://www.dogshope.com/adoption_application2.html

animal.description:
Ramen is a stunning 3 year old, 35 pound Pointer/hound . He is currently in obedience training with Tug Dogs and has made an incredible process. He needs an experienced handler and owner who understands Ramens needs and his limitations. He is dog reactive , so he needs a confident people to redirect him as he see's another dog approaching . Ramens adopter needs to understand he’s not a social butterfly with strangers. Ramen will need a structure life style and daily crate training. He is very food motivate which is a great start for success .He’s an awesome dog with a lot of love to give. He is typically a one dog only family without no other pets and NO small young children.  When we rescued Ramen will noticed after running and playing hard he would lift one of his back legs up. He was seen by orthopedic veterinarian for an old injury that occured before Ramen coming into our rescue. Since the injury was already healed/time has passed, surgery wasn't an option for Ramen. 

PLEASE CHECK OUT HIS VIDEO @ WWW.4DOGSFARMRESCUE.ORG 

Ramen is up to date on vaccines and neutered. 

Adoption fee:$475.00

Meet Casper!  This adorable boy is looking for a loving home.  He is friendly boy that loves to snuggle and gives kisses.  He is a smart boy that is potty-trained.  Casper would do best in a home without other pets or small children.  

The NAWS Dog Adoption Program operates as a rescue versus a shelter.  We believe in matching the right dog with the appropriate family based on each specific dog or family's needs.  To achieve this, we believe in spending the appropriate amount of time with each family to allow for enough interaction time with potential adopters.  This cannot be achieved if people stop by unexpectedly to meet our dogs.  Please e-mail Stacy at stacy@nawsus.org to setup a day or time to meet with one of our adoption counselors and our potential adoptees.  Thank you!

animal.description:
Meet Bucky!

Hello, I'm Bucky. For the first time in my whole life I'm starting to feel special, and not just because my special needs. I was born somewhere around June 2019, making me about a year and a half old, and I weigh about 60 pounds. I was recently rescued from the place I was living, in a shop, not being well cared for, and now I get to find a family who will love me for me! You see, I'm likely a distemper survivor, which isn't as common as one would think, but there isn't a test to see if that's what is going on, but it's probable. So, I might be a little wobbly, but I'm really just a "normal" dog. I'm housetrained, and rarely have accidents anymore. I am also crate trained, although I do need a little help getting in, but if you just toss a couple treats in there, that helps me alot. I love people of all ages and even snuggle up for nap time with the 4 year old human that lives in my foster home. But, since I do wobble and fall sometimes, maybe I shouldn't be around really little ones unless you will be close, so I don't knock them over or fall on them. I love playing with other dogs, or at least trying, but I have some limitations and I would need to live with a very patient dog if there is one in my new home. One that understands I'm not trying to hurt them or be mean, and isn't scared of my unique walk. There aren't any cats in my foster home, but I'm almost certain I would be able to meet one for the right family!

I'd love a family who isn't super active since I can't go on long walks. I love to be by my humans! I really need a family who promises to always be patient with me. I will make for a good snuggle bug for my forever people. Even though I can't do all the things other dogs can, I sure do try, and I can for sure still love with my whole being! I'm sure my love and goofy walk will be enough for someone, right?

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

animal.description:
Ramiro is a 4 year old Malinois who was originally purchased abroad and trained for narcotics detection. He worked for a private company for a number of years, and then was donated to a small police department near St Louis. Unfortunately, he is unable to pass narcotic certification and, as a result, cannot have a career as a K9. He does not have apprehension/agitation/aggression training, and was never trained in any sort of bite work. He has a solid ball drive, and has been able to get along with other male and female dogs.

Ramiro is on Apoquil daily for skin allergies. He has shown a high prey drive, so no cats or small animals. Past owner reported he has interacted with children from 1 year to 12 years old and is non-reactive to strangers; MAD Rescue has not confirmed this information or child-tested this dog. He is reported to be skittish around large 18-wheeler trucks and loud sirens. He also has a bit of separation anxiety so someone who works from home or isn't gone for long periods would be preferable.

Ramiro loves tennis balls and will fetch until his human is too tired. Ramiro keeps a clean kennel and likes to sleep in his crate when he gets tired. This is a beautiful dog who needs an involved owner who isn't a push-over.

If you are interested in adopting this pet please complete an application at this link https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24689/generic . 

We are an official 501C3 organization that does not have a physical location. Our home address is in Michigan, however, the majority of our dogs are not located in Michigan. The physical location of each our our dogs is posted with the name of the pet or in the title area. If you are within 4 hours of the pet, please be prepared to pick the pet up. We do provide transport assistance up to 650 miles; however, the applicant must drive 50% of the total distance of the transport. 

The information that we have available is in our posting. If you would like to discuss this animal additionally please fill out this application. Applications that are completed in our process and being considered as a match will speak to the foster home to gain more information about our adoptable dog. 

If you have questions about this pet please contact sandra@madrescueinc.org. 

You may also call our toll free number at 844-MAD-RESQ or 844-623-7377. 

Additional information about all of our dogs for adoption can be located at our website MAD Rescue Inc

animal.description:
Dog Name: Sampson 
Sex: Male 
Breed: Pit Mix 
Age: 8
Weight: approx 55lbs
Medical Needs: None known. (He is getting neutered and a vet checkup on 01/22/2021)

Housebroken: Yes but can dribble when he gets excited. He is also VERY interested in all of the smells left around the house so he wears a belly band as of right now. That will hopefully change after his neuter. 

Crate trained: Yes, he goes right in. Occasionally he will make some noise but that is improving. 
Good in the car: Yes
Good on a leash: Yes, with pinch collar. He can be strong when he gets on a scent he wants to check out 
Energy level: Low (ZERO interest in toys) 
Need a fenced in yard: Not necessary with daily walks. If left outside in our yard, hell just sit at the door and cry to come back in the house. 

Dog Friendly: Said to be. Hes still in the 2 week shutdown at our house. I can update with how introductions go with resident dogs.

If yes, does your foster need another dog in its adoptive homes? No

Cat Friendly? No, he was VERY interested in getting to the cat on the other side of the fence when tested. 

Kid Friendly: Yes, has previously lived with kids 
If yes, what's the youngest child you'd recommend they be placed with? 

Special traits that make your foster special or that we need to know about them?
Sampson is a handsome guy looking for a forever family to call his own. He is a real quick learner and has been practicing his sit-stays on place. He is very gentle with taking treats but has no toy drive. He is such a gentleman that he doesnt even jump on people or try to get on the furniture. He is still settling in here at his foster home but so far he has been very sweet without showing much enthusiasm over anything other than treats and his food. We will be updating in the coming weeks as we learn more about him.

animal.description: Hi, my name is Jeffrey. I like to stay humble, but my foster parents think I'm the best. I am a 2 year old black lab mix and the sweetest boy you will ever meet. I love to cuddle especially while you work from home, but I am also perfectly content in my crate. Anytime you leave my sight, I will cuddle with your slippers instead. I hardly ever whine and never bark, so I make a great companion. I do a happy dance when I am about to go on a long walk and am getting more used to my leash. Always keep it tight because sometimes I want to slip out to be free. I am really good at reading the room, so if you want to play, I'll play, but if you want to chill, I'll chill. I am almost completely housebroken. I am great with other dogs and kids and everyone in general. Looking for a loving furever home that will feed me peanut butter. I don't know if you believe in love at first sight, but I will make you believe.

animal.description:
Meet Elvis! 

Siblings Elvis and Pru have had a rough few months! This duo of 2 year old Rat Terrier mixes were adopted from us as puppies. They had been found together in the countryside fending for themselves and theyve been together ever since! Sadly, their mom developed serious health issues earlier this year and has had to come to the heart wrenching realization that she can no longer provide them with the life they deserve. So a few days after Thanksgiving, Elvis and Pru said goodbye to their mom who loves them so very very much and moved back into their original foster home. Foster mom Arla had actually since stepped back from fostering but she had kept in touch with Elvis and Pru (she even pet sat for them a few months ago while their mom was in the hospital), so she didnt even miss a beat in saying she would absolutely take care of them and help ease the loss of their mom. Visibly sad and confused, Pru perked right up that first night when she saw Arla and realized where she was and who was there waiting for her!

We know how difficult it can be to find an extra special family willing to open their hearts and homes to two dogs at once, but Elvis and Pru have never spent a day apart and have already suffered enough loss in their lifetime. Its really important to us, and to their mom who loves them so very much, that they be allowed to stay together. If they cant have their mom, at least they can have each other. They are great with other dogs and actually find comfort in a pack, so to speak. So even though they have each other, we have determined that they do need at least one other dog in the home with them. They would also prefer a home without children - older teens are ok. We just know there is a special someone out there who needs these babies as much as Elvis and Pru need them. Is that special someone you? Email adrienne@rescuemega.org or fill out an adoption application on our website- www.rmgdogs.org

animal.description:
(DOB 10/25/2020) Pecan is an adorable hound mix puppy. She is currently about 20 lbs, but we estimate that she will be about 50 - 60 lbs., full grown. She is super sweet, smart and a very quick learner. She is full of kisses and is an absolute wiggle butt when being held as she wants to be put back down to run and play as soon as she can. With her fun and playful nature and her continuing socialization needs, we are only looking for homes with another dog-friendly dog and a fenced yard ... or an active family that will take her and her dog-sibling for walks. Also, because she is a young puppy that accidentally nips and scratches, we are looking for homes with children 10 and older. 

As part of Pecan's $275 adoption fee, she will be spayed, microchipped, up to date on age appropriate vaccines, and current on her monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventatives. If you have questions about this sweet little girl, you can email Dogteam@pawsforlifenc.org. If you wish to adopt Pecan, you can fill in an online application for her under the Adopt a Pet Tab on our website: www.pawsforlifenc.org.

Dog friendly

Loves kids
House trained

Dixie was surrendered to a full west Texas shelter in absolutely deplorable condition. Truly her owners should have been prosecuted by it was west Texas so likely they already have another dog. We can only guess she was purchased as a puppy and put in the yard when she got larger and they didn't trainer her. Dixie is a complete DOLL! She has no reason to love humans or want to snuggle with everyone, but she does. She was pulled and went to a fantastic foster and now she is making her way up to us! She's a total sweetie and is going to make someone an amazing family member.

If you are interested in meeting a dog or cat, we require an adoption application. Apply for a DOG: http://www.citydogsrescuedc.org/adoptable-dogs.html

Interested in saving more lives? Foster a dog today! Learn more, see our list of dogs needing foster, and apply, https://www.citydogsrescuedc.org/foster-a-city-dog.html

City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is a foster based rescue in Washington, DC. We do not have a shelter. We focus on local adoptions in DC and the metro area of Maryland and Virginia. CDR&CK has a thorough adoption process in order to find the best possible fit for each of our dogs and cats (we do not operate under a first-come, first served model).

Upon accepting a new cat or dog into the organization, we provide a basic vet visit that includes necessary vaccinations, disease screenings, deworming, microchips, and spay/neuter (unless specified). We do not provide a comprehensive medical exam prior to adoption. As a result, sickness, injury, and disability may exist unbeknownst to CDR&CK. City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is not responsible for payment of any vet care, including known and unknown medical conditions once a cat or dog is adopted from us. 
Dog specific: Rabies, DHPP, Bordatella vaccines. They are tested for HW, Lyme, Ehrlichia, Anaplasmosis.

Most cats and dogs will have a house training accident in the initial days in their new home and we cannot guarantee any pet is housebroken or crate trained.

We also update our Facebook page daily with new cats and dogs.

Meet Copper2
Breed: Chihuahua mix
Age: 1 year old
Sex: Neutered male
Size: approx. 8 lbs

Other Dogs: Yes
Kids: Yes, over the age of 8
Cats/Small Animals: Yes
House trained: Yes
Adoption Fee: $250.00

Copper is a young, 1-2 year old, make Chi mix who weighs about 8 lbs. He is housetrained and will signal to go out but should be on a schedule we first arriving in a new home. He is good with other dogs but is more of an observer as he is really shy. We think he will interact once he becomes comfortable as he came from a home with multiple dogs. 
He is crate trained and will sleep in his crate or on his dog bed. He is a friendly guy but will need to to adjust to a new environment as he tends to be a bit cautious and slow to warm-up. He does like going for walks and is still learning how to be on leash as it is a new experience for him. Because he gets nervous he has a tendency to vomit when on a car ride. He doesn't have any formal training but is smart, young and a willing learner. He is not a chewer but likes to steal items to bring to his bed.

He is a pretty quiet dog but will bark when people come to the door.
He is respectful of cats and has not been around children at his foster's home so because he is shy, we are going to recommend children over the age of 8.
He is looking for a calm home with people willing to spend time with him and let him come out of his shell.

We are complying with all recommendations set forth by our governor. At this time our office is not open to the public and we will not be having public adoption events. We will continue to have private meet and greets ONLY.
If you are interested in any of the dogs we have available, please make sure to download an adoption application (from this site), fill it out, and email it to foothillcoordinator@gmail.com. We will be going over the applications for best fit for the dog, it is not first come first serve. If your application is chosen, we will set up a private meet and greet with you. Please DO NOT contact the office for available dogs or private "meet and greets."

The NAWS Dog Adoption Program operates as a rescue versus a shelter.  We believe in matching the right dog with the appropriate family based on each specific dog or family's needs.  To achieve this, we believe in spending the appropriate amount of time with each family to allow for enough interaction time with potential adopters.  This cannot be achieved if people stop by unexpectedly to meet our dogs. animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Winnie arrived here from Arkansas at the end of November with her one newborn puppy. Because Winnie was in mama mode and protective of her puppy, we have only just started to recently see her true personalitywhich is wonderful! Winnie is a large lap dog that would love nothing more that to lounge on a comfy bed or couch next to you. For the first month Winnie spent most of her time separate from the resident dogs and had a few negative run ins with our crabby, ten-year-old, ten lb. resident dog. Their "fights" looked and sounded worse that they were, and Winnie always seemed remorseful after. She is a sensitive girl and just wants to please you. She has recently started to play with the resident puppy. They love to run around the yard, wrestle and play tug-of-war. Winnie likes to use her paws to get your attention and does jump up. We are working with her on her manners. She also seems to have some separation anxiety and is very verbal and hyper when you get home. Winnie needs to have a harness on when walking. She is strong and is working on her leash manners. She is also a good jumper so a yard with a fence is needed. She does have some guarding with food and some toys. We feed her away from the other dogs. She seems to be getting better with this. Winnie would do best in a home with a well-mannered dog or as the only dog. We are not sure about cats. We don't know anything about Winnie prior to her arriving in Minnesota so she should go to a home without small children.

Adoption fee includes: Full veterinary exam, alter, prepaid microchip, dewormed, Rabies vaccine, DAPP vaccine, Bordetella vaccine, 4DX

, flea/tick and heartworm preventative while in rescue. Adoption fee: $495.00

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. Copy and paste the link to access the sign-up genius for an appointment: https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet for dogs and https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1 for cats.

For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to adoptioncenter@homewardtrails.org

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE:
http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Meet Daryl! This handsome male mixed breed comes to Homeward Trails from Fayette County, WV after he surrendered by his previous owner. He is a sweet boy, about 3 years old, looking for a family with lots of love and a little patience. He can be a little shy, but we know he's full of love and just adjusting to his new surroundings. Hopefully his forever home is soon to be! 

Come meet him this weekend at our adoption center.

Adoption Coordinator: Center staff
Location: Adoption Center
The adoption fee for this dog is $475. This fee INCLUDES spay/neuter and microchip.

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description:
Duke is the PERFECT companion for someone who lives by themselves, or a small family looking for a dog who gives companionship! A huge cuddle bug, Duke loves spending time at his person's side. He does just fine being left in the home by himself, and behaves very well without being crated. He loves sleeping in a dog bed or in the bed with his human if they are welcome to it. Duke takes loyalty very seriously, and is devoted to his caretaker. While he is not dog reactive, he is not a fan of sharing the love and can sometimes be a bit competitive, so he would like do best as the only dog in a home, or paired with a calm, passive dog that does not ask for a lot of attention. He has not been tested with cats. 

Duke behaves rather well on walks, not reacting to other dogs or squirrels. He does, however, still get tangled in the leash so would do well with some training to help get him used to that. He is house-trained. 

Duke would pair well with a home of 1- 3 people who can give him a lot of attention and affection. We do not think Duke would enjoy a home with small children, so we are considering applications of families with kids 12+. 

Please submit an application on our website, or email 'messagemarybeth@gmail.com' for more information. 

Location: Foster 
Adoption Coordinator : Mary Beth Maggio 

The adoption fee for this dog is $475. This fee includes spay/neuter and microchip.

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

If Interested please fill out an application at www.camorescue.com

animal.description:
I'm Moon Shadow, a 4 yr old, approximately 45-50 lbs tri colored Coonhound mix. My foster mom says I am a GREAT dog! I have a sweet, but timid, personality- typical of hounds. I am house trained, so no middle of the night trips outside or accidents to clean up. I do well in my crate- I sleep in it with the door open.

I am good with other dogs, but all I really want is to be with people more than anyone else, so I would be quite content as an only dog too. I CANNOT live in a home with cats- nope, not for me.  I haven't been around small kids, but I love my teenage foster sisters .My foster mom says I am doing fine on the leash, but I might still need some practice.

Oh and one more thing- I would LOVE a house where I am allowed on the couch- I do love to be cozy! I am so excited to have a furever home of my very own! If you think it might be with you, please apply!


If interested in adopting please fill out our no obligation online application at www.puppypawsrescue.org 

Note: Our rescue requires that all adopter's current and prior animals are up-to-date on vaccinations (DHLPP & Rabies)  and preventatives (heartworm and flea and tick), unless there is a medical reason not allowing it. All animals in your household should be spayed or neutered unless medically indicated that they should not be or are currently still too young.

animal.description:
****COURTESY POSTING**** (we'll happily put you in contact with foster)

If you don’t know what love is, you will once you meet this young lady. A year ago Frida was saved by a rescue near a village in Skopje, Macedonia. She was emaciated and missing one of her front legs. After getting a vet care and good nutritional food, she soon became a very happy, joyful dog, playing and running with rescue kennel dogs. This 3 legged Miracle dog never lost her faith in humanity and doesn’t let having 3 legs and a small heart murmur (treated by medication with no issue) to get in the way of anything. She is a happy girl, loves everyone, kids and dogs. Frida loves massages, running to play, walks, play with other dogs and she is also very calm and gentle dog. Her kindness, sweetness and full of joy makes her a very special dog. She gives so much love that you wouldn’t think it is possible. 

 This three legged angel is looking for her perfect forever home where they would love and care for her unconditionally. If you are interested adopting or have any questions regarding Frida please contact Silvia 914-519-8771 or Silvia.pogosyan@gmail.com

animal.description:
Teddy is a 2 year old Male Schnoodle, weighing 14 pounds (The Schnoodle is a cross between a Miniature Schnauzer and a Poodle.)  Teddy was pulled by rescue from a high kill shelter where he was given an euthanasia date due to resource guarding his food bowl.  For this reason we are searching for an ADULT ONLY, QUIET home.  

Teddy is doing well in his foster home with structure and routine.  Teddy has suffered physical abuse in his past and does not respond well to abusive/harsh discipline.  He does well with positive reinforcement training.  Teddy bonds quickly to his person and would like a home where his human spends a lot of time with him.  He is a true companion that follows his person wherever they go in the house.  Teddy is young and will need an active human to go on walks and play with.  He doesn't like to be left alone so a home where he will not be left alone for long hours of the day would be best.  ***Consider your time at home commitment AFTER covid-19 restrictions are lifted.  While working from home now, you will need to think about the time spent away from home after returning to work in the future.   Teddy likes dogs his size or smaller.  He is fearful of large dogs.  He will chase cats.  We would like Teddy to be the only pet in his new home where he will get all the focus and attention he is craving.  


Schnoodles are charming, funny and smart, and their alert nature — thanks to that double dose of Schnauzer and Poodle attentiveness — makes them excellent watchdogs. They are small dogs and typically have a curly coat that MUST be groomed by a professional regularly, every 6-8 weeks.  

A home with Schnoodle experience or Schnauzer experience is preferred. Schnauzer's can be temperamental so a person who is aware of their personality and loves them unconditionally would be great.

Teddy's adoption fee is $300.00 which includes his neuter, current on vaccines including Rabies, de-wormed, Heart worm tested Negative, current on heart worm and flea prevention.  

If your home meets the requirements stated above and you want to meet Teddy, the first step is to complete an adoption application online at furgetmenotrescue.org   *In State of Ohio adoptions only.

animal.description:
Sadie is a 7 year old Boxer with a tail. Sadie is looking for a perfect home. She had a wonderful life until a little over a year old. Her mother was dealing with mental illness and committed suicide. The boyfriend tried to keep Sadie & the other dog but was not able. They ended up in animal control at least twice. We are not sure the outcome of the other dog. We were asked to take Sadie when she'd been in the shelter for 6 months. She was very skinny from intestinal worms. She was previously microchipped and spayed. She was also heartworm negative. 
We instantly knew something was wrong. She has a slight head tilt. She also walks odd in the backend. We believe she was hit by a car at some point in her life. This doesn't affect her at all though. Her pupils do not constrict. It is called iris atrophy. She was diagnosed by an ophthalmologist vet. There is no treatment. She might have some sight defects but we rarely notice anything wrong. The vet noticed a few slight differences in her spine xray. She is on omeprazole 40 mg nightly. It reduces the fluid in the brain. I've noticed less of a head tilt since she's been on it. She saw a neurologist. The only way to absolutely diagnose would be an MRI. The issue is most problems are not treatable so it is a waste of money. The only thing we've noticed is she does not like loud noises. She really despises metal noises like a metal bowl hitting the floor or kennel. She does not like the noise a tag makes on the collar. She will need a tag that slips on the collar instead of a normal id tag. She had a dental with dental xray. She had 3 teeth pulled. She also had a lot of her gums removed. She has gingivitis hyperplasia. This is a genetic issue. Her parents shouldn't have been bred. It is very painful. She might need yearly dentals to correct this or it might never come back. It is something the owner must be able to afford if it returns. It is not something that can be ignored. We personally use Dr. Hill at Maple Small Animal Clinic in New Orleans, LA. He is great at dentals. She is up to date on her vaccinations, heartworm prevention and flea prevention. She is heartworm negative, microchipped and spayed. She had a negative fecal. She was treated for a urinary infection. She had a great exam recently. 
She would prefer daily walks. She is a great snuggler and couch dog. But she does have some energy to burn. She does not like to be outside without you long. She wants to potty and come right inside. But if you are outside with her there are no issues. She loves to give kisses. She's great in the car. She's great on the leash. She is cat aggressive. She has no issues with the pigs. She has aggression issues with anything pit like. She obviously had issues in her past with a pit. She has no issues walking around dogs. She just cannot get super close to a dog that is pit like. She does love playing with dogs. I'd honestly prefer to have her in an only dog home. Her previous family taught her sit. She is crate trained and housetrained. She weighs 40 lbs. She will need to remain slender build to help her back. She is currently on Dasuquin for her joints. We also recommend Nutramax fish oil and adequan injections for her joints. 
She is located in New Orleans, LA. Her adoption fee is $150. Email animalhelperneworleans@gmail.com

Here is an article about her mother: https://www.wwltv.com/article/news/local/northshore/pregnant-and-with-mental-illness-her-family-begged-for-help/289-162269b0-b09f-4597-92a7-7bd09e332d72

animal.description:
This is “Bear”! Bear is 14 months old, male, full blooded German Shepard. He has been neutered, is house trained, up to date on all his shots and heart worm negative. He is a large dog that just wants to be your shadow- he will follow you everywhere and keep you company by contently laying at your feet if you are working from home. Bear does great on a leash and needs to be able to run off energy- either on lots of walks or in a yard. He is good with other dogs but we don’t know about cats. He would do best in a home with preteens and above. This dog is amazing, gorgeous, and deserves a great home.

This dog is a Benefactor Dog. His/her increased adoption fee will allow them to act as a benefactor to other dogs in our care that require special medical care and a better chance at adoption.

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (that application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

 The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information.

2021 Adoption Fee Scale:
Benefactor Puppies under 12 months - $500
Benefactor Dogs over 12 months - $400


*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

*Any breed labels used by Take Paws Rescue, its employees/volunteers, or on vet records provided cannot be guaranteed.  Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

animal.description:
Cece is an adorable, affectionate Staffy mix who is 11 months old and weighs 40 lbs.  She came to BarkVille severely injured & requiring extensive surgery on her neck after being violently attacked by another dog.  She was found with another young female dog who was also scarred & injured, and we fear that both girls had been used as bait dogs. Thankfully, Cece's surgeries went well and she (and her companion) were both placed in wonderful foster homes where they are putting on weight & regaining their health & confidence daily.  Although her wounds have healed, CeCe will always need to wear a harness instead of a regular collar or slip lead due to the sensitivity around her neck.  Her foster mom says CeCe loves to nap all day and has started showing interest in durable chew toys, but will destroy stuffies.  She is a loving, gentle cuddle bug and is good with children.  She is housebroken, spayed, fully vaccinated & microchipped.  She is crate trained, but is not a fan of the crate, so she's looking for a home with a person/family who are home often so that her crate time will be minimal.

For more information about CeCe, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to adopt this sweet girl, please submit an application for her at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/applications

animal.description: Buster is a happy, energetic pup who loves people. He has never met a stranger. He loves to get scratched and to go on long walks. He has a lot of energy and would make a great hiking companion, but he also enjoys time alone and knows how to entertain himself. Buster gets overexcited easily and becomes jumpy, especially when people are trying to put his harness on. He can also be reactive toward other dogs while he's on a leash. He has been working on staying calm during times of excitement, and he has developed a routine with his caregivers at Dogtown. Buster was born in 2017. He has some mild skin and respiratory issues, but they don't slow him down. He is very smart and will need a person or family who will continue helping him work on being calm. An active home where he can be the one and only, without other dogs or cats, would be ideal for him. Life is already exciting for Buster, but nothing would make him happier than finding a home to call his own.

Please review our Adoption Process before filling out an application. If you would like to try a Foster to Adopt trial, please fill out an Adoption Application.

If you are only interested in temporarily Fostering one of our rescues, please fill out a Foster Application.

Meet Coffee!UPDATE 1-20-21: Here is what Coffee's foster mom has to say about him:'Coffee is so sweet and very playful. He enjoys his family time and focused attention with us, but also can play alone and entertain himself. He is almost completely crate trained and getting closer to being house trained (he still has the occasional pee accident). He is learning to sit and give paw and enjoys playing fetch and playing with his toys. He is both food motivated and toy motivated, and of course motivated by love and affection. He is also now leash trained and enjoys going for walks, he also does well on car rides. He enjoys children and has done well with our 3 children ages 3, 5, and 7, as well as our cat, and the neighbors dog.'ORIGINAL RESCUE STORY: Coffee was found on the streets of Ensenada Mexico and we are still learning about his personality. We will post more information about him as we learn more from his current foster family. We do know he is a typical young pup with lots of energy, which is the case with most pups his age. He is great with kids, dogs, and cats!
Because of COVID-19, sterilization appointments have been difficult to schedule. Coffee will both be sterilized on Thursday, January 28th in the 92109 area of San Diego. This means he can only be adopted to local families in the San Diego area to ensure they are able to take their newly adopted puppy to the pre-scheduled surgery appointment, and then pick him up at the end of the day after surgery.
Therefore, please do NOT submit an application if you are not local to San Diego and able to attend the appointment shown above. If you would like to adopt and live outside of San Diego area, you are welcome to wait until his sterilization surgery has been completed to see if he is still available at that time.
If you are interested in adopting Coffee, please submit an online adoption application at www.arwob.org. Don't wait!

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE:
http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Meet Reno! This handsome male mixed breed comes to Homeward Trails from Fayette County, WV after he was picked up as a stray. He is a sweet boy, about 2 years old, looking for a family with lots of love. Hopefully his forever home is soon to be! 

Come meet him this weekend at our adoption center.

Adoption Coordinator: Center staff
Location: Adoption Center
The adoption fee for this dog is $475. This fee INCLUDES spay/neuter and microchip.

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

Lacee comes to Golden Retriever Rescue Resource from an owner who didn’t have the time to provide this sweet girl. Her owners knew GRRR would find a great home that would foreve3r home who would give her what she needs to be a great, loving dog. 

Lacee is a 5 years old golden doodle. She had been on medication, but now is med free. Her foster mom believes that she wasn’t very socialized, as she gets very excited and will jump up. All of her behavior is correctable with your time and awesome training. Due to her jumping, it is recommended that she not be in a home with little kids, as she may inadvertently knock them right down. 

Lacee is cheerful, loving and is just looking for a cuddle buddy-sofa or bed. She loves playing with toys and her foster home dog pack mates. Lacee is headed to a foster-to-adopt home this week. If she does become available for adoption, we'll list this on her page on our website at www.gr-rescue.org.

To adopt a Golden that you see here, please go to the Golden Retriever Rescue Resource website at www.gr-rescue.org  Read our adoption policies. If you qualify for this dogs adoption and the adoption policies, please write us for an adoption application at grrradoption@yahoo.com  Please provide your city and zip code. Please note, we only adopt to select areas within Ohio, Michigan and Indiana where we can do a home visit by a trusted volunteer. 

Please read our adoption policies on our website prior to inquiring for an adoption application. Thank you!

animal.description:
"A lap dog in her own mind." Sweet, sweet Cassie, no one wants to tell her she is not a lap dog. Cassie will follow you around, waiting for the opportunity to give you hugs and kisses. She is a Pyr who readily accepts belly and ear rubs. She longs to be close to you and likes to meet new people.

Cassie, born around March 2020 and weighing about 65 lbs, was rescued by the Great Pyrenees Rescue Society from a Texas animal shelter after her owner surrendered her. The family had to move and could not take her.

Cassie is house broken, crate trained, uses the pet door, walks nicely on a leash, and rides fine in a car. Her foster mom said, "Cassie had no interest in the elderly cats and was tolerant after a slow introduction with the resident female canine. She can be very picky when meeting other dogs.

Cassie would thrive in an active family with older, considerate kids. She needs a yard to run and play in and daily walks. Cassie is an intelligent and treat-motivated Pyr who needs continuous training and socializing. She will require a confident leader in her family, familiar with Pyr behavior and traits. If you would like to adopt Cassie into your family, please complete an Adoption Application.

PUPPIES ARE ONLY PLACED IN HOMES WITH YOUTHFUL, PLAYFUL RESIDENT DOGS.

Our requirements for puppy adoption are simple and necessary.

	Our puppies are not livestock guardians, they are family pets that live inside the family home.
	Puppies must be placed in homes with a youthful, adult resident dog of similar size. This gives the puppy a mentor and a solid foundation for becoming part of the family.
	Puppies are only adopted to homes with someone at home at least part of the day. If no one is home for 6-8 hours at a time, please do not apply.
	Preference is always given to those with Great Pyrenees experience.
	Applicants must have secure, visible fencing and a socialization plan in place.
	The fastest way to be considered for a puppy is to fill out an application. Adoption is not first come, first served. GPRS and its fosters work diligently to find the right fit for each and every unique dog and puppy.

Adoption Fee $450 (Adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm test, rabies, distemper, parvo and health certificate for travel). Northwest adopters pay the cost of transport to independent transport service ($225). Adoption applications can be found on our website at https://www.greatpyreneesrescuesociety.org.

ADOPTION, FOSTERING, AND DONATIONS are just some of the ways you can help a rescued dog. We have worked hard to cultivate a large network of volunteers to save this majestic breed. While monetary donations are always much appreciated, you can also help by donating your time as a GPRS foster or volunteer!

animal.description:
Carly is a lively, curious and playful young lady who loves to play ball! The intensity of Carly's zoomies is unmatched - she just LOVES to run and play with other dogs! Tag and Tug are the best games ever! She would love to go to a home that has at least one other dog, and she also likes cats! She likes to play with happy young cats, and learned to ignore the old grouchy ones in one of her foster homes. Carly loves her chosen humans and shows it by staying near them all day long, napping next to them, "talking" to them about exciting things, and wanting to be part of all their activities.

However, Carly is still very nervous around new people after coming from a place where she likely had little interaction with humans. She has come a long way, but is still learning that hands and petting aren't scary. Carly is working hard on her leash skills and basic obedience, but she has mastered targeting, coming when called, going to her place/mat, and has almost fully mastered potty training! Carly would do best with a patient family, with older or no kids, willing to continue her socialization training.

Given the slow transition Carly will need at home, she is a participant in our Foster-to-Adopt program and the lucky recipient of our post adoption scholarship! Her adopter(s) will be guided through the process of acclimating her to her new home, and will receive donated training from K9 Wisdom post-adoption. Ask our adoptions team about this program by calling 970-484-8516.

animal.description:
Meet SCOOBY! He is a gorgeous SWEETHEART! More details below.

**During the current health situation**

If you are interested in ADOPTING from the EDISON ANIMAL SHELTER, please email the shelter manager, Becky Snyder at rsnyder@edisonnj.org and she will send you an application to fill out and discuss potentially setting up a meeting. The subject of the email should be "Adoption - Pet's Name". Thank you. Be safe and stay healthy.

ADOPT ME!  Say hello to SCOOBY. He is a gorgeous SWEETHEART who is about 2 years old. He is fun, playful and very, very energetic. 

Scooby needs a home with a fenced yard and someone willing to take the time to give him the attention and training he so desperately needs. He is not the dog for you if you live in an apartment or condo without a yard that he can run in. He likes to be with people, so just putting him out in a yard alone will not work. He will just sit and wait for you to come out and play with him. With the training he needs, it may be best if he is the only dog so he could focus.

All of our shelter dogs and cats are spayed/neutered, microchipped and up to date on their vaccinations prior to adoption.

Hi, I’m Ambia! I’m a 48lb lab/terrier mix.  I’m a sweet, friendly  girl who loves attention, giving kisses, tasty treats and being around people.  I’m very good about taking those yummy treats from you gently and will quickly sit when I see one in your hand!  Here at the shelter, I like to run and explore the yard when outside but am pretty laid back when I get to come in a hang out with the staff.

I came to the shelter with my 2 girls and we’ve had fun here but we’re all ready to move on to our forever homes. The shelter staff would be happy to reintroduce me to one if you’d like to add me to your cat-friendly home to see if I’d be a good match for your family.

animal.description:
Ralphie is young (about 1 year old) pointer mix that will be joining us in Maine January 30th. He was hit by a car in Louisiana and had to have FHO surgery to keep the leg. He does have a limp when he walks that will be permanent. 

Even with his injury this does not slow down Ralphie. He is energetic and loves everyone. He gets along with other energetic dogs but does not do well with cats...he will chase them. 

He loves to go for walks and does well on a leash. He is crate-trained and mostly housebroken. 

Ralphie would do best in a home without cats or small children. He gets along with most dogs but with his energy older dogs may not appreciate. He would love someone that could give him a home with some hiking or swimming. He would also love a good massage.






Adoption fees cover age specific vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm/lyme/ehrlichia test, worming and transport fees. 

Adoption fees: 
Through 6 months of age $450; 
7 months to through 5 years $400; 
6 years and under 9 years $325: bonded pairs are $500; 
9 years and older $250: bonded pairs are $300 

This dog is available unless it is marked as Pending, meaning Pending Adoption. This dog is in foster care locally, ONLY if Maine or New Hampshire is listed next to the dogs name; otherwise, the dog is still waiting with our partner rescue for an adoption or foster home in New England. 

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior dogs have a history of being kept up to date on rabies and distemper, have had annual heartworm tests, and are on heartworm preventative at least 6 months of the year. Current pets must by spayed/neutered. 

Imported dogs are transported on a USDA approved transport with a Health Certificate. All imported dogs are quarantined 14 days prior to getting on transport.

He is a friendly and lovable dog! He will moan and groan if he is not the one getting affection and will completely melt once you begin to pet him. He loves belly rubs and getting his hair brushed. One of Limburger's favorite things to do is to destroy stuffed animals! He gets the biggest kick out of taking the squeaky toy out and is very proud when he does! This big boy loves to play! He will run away with our shoes just to get a reaction out of us and we have to negotiate for them back. He has never destroyed anything, he is just very playful! A very big plus is that Limburger is house and crate trained! He is like clockwork so we never have to worry about any accidents inside the home. I weigh approximately 75 lbs. animal.description:
Nipper is a two-year old, 9 lb, male Chihuahua that came to us as a stray no one ever claimed. He is a very bouncy, active and playful boy. He is nicknamed Nipper as he is very mouthy and has a tendency to jump and grab your fingers with his teeth and why we have no children on him. He isn't doing that to be mean but some folks won't like that at all and he does need to learn a bit better manners. NOT housetrained and NOT good with other male dogs.
ADOPTION FEES Dogs & Puppies.....$100.00 . This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more.
The first step to do an adoption is to do our Adoption Application here: https://www.elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html
IMPORTANT - we respond to your emailed applications and queries via email back to you. Please make sure you have either added our email (hselco@bellsouth.net) to your contact list or that you routinely check your SPAM folder for our response just to be safe. If we do not receive a timely response we simply move on to another applicant.
Yes, there are sometimes exceptions to our normal fee for older dogs or special cases. Some of our pets have also been lovingly sponsored by caring people and we will let the approved adopter know about that at the point of adoption. Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description. This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.
Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net

animal.description:
PHOTOS:  Virtually all of our dogs have online PHOTO ALBUMS through SmugMug with LOTS of additional pictures.  Just copy and paste the link below into your browser (or simply type it in) and then search for the dog's "gallery" by name

          http://adoptasleddog.smugmug.com

VIDEOS:  In addition to photo albums, almost every dog has a video which will give you a much better "feel" for his or her personality.  NOTE:  In the new Petfinder format, it has become quite a bit more difficult to find and to play videos.  Please PAGE THROUGH the photos, looking for a photo overlaid in the center with a "play" arrow inside a circle.  This icon is white, so it can be difficult to see. 
 In many (most) cases, the video is the last photo displayed as you page through.  Just click on that photo and it will play.  Please make sure you CHECK ON THE PETFINDER VIDEO ICON, above, to see a video of this wonderful dog!  Our videos will include, at a minimum, whatever info we had on the dog upon (or shortly after) his/her arrival into our program.  There will sometimes be video updates as well.  And in every case, our Adoptions Coordinator can be emailed at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to answer questions and provide the most current information we have on the dog.  

NOTES:  Please see video or contact our Adoptions Coordinator at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM.

ADOPTION DONATION:  $250  Before adoption, all Northern Lights dogs (regardless of whether Petfinder's symbols appear) are spayed or neutered, microchipped, heartworm negative, fully vaccinated and tested/treated for known parasites.
 
WHAT TO DO IF YOU WANT TO ADOPT THIS DOG:  Email us at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to request an application and get started.  WE DO NOT HAVE AN ONLINE APPLICATION - you will have to request one via email.  We will review your application to determine if there is a good fit between you and/or your family and this dog.  We may suggest another dog or dog(s) if we can offer a better fit in terms of lifestyle, experience, other pets, etc.  A vet check, reference checks, and a home visit will be conducted before an adoption can be considered for approval.  
 
NORTHERN LIGHTS DOES NOT HAVE A PHYSICAL SHELTER.  We are a nonprofit rescue organization comprised of individuals who open their private homes to foster dogs in need of a second chance..  When fosters are not available, we often pay to board a dog until space is available.  New fosters and donations to pay for boarding are always desperately needed us.  Email us at KATYLIED2@AOL.COM if you are interested in donating or for information on fostering.
 
FAQ:  For information regarding our organization, as well as adoption policies and practices, please visit our Petfinder Home Page at WWW.NORTHERNLIGHTS.PETFINDER.COM.
 
 
NOTICE:  In the vast majority of cases, the dogs in our program and rescued from shelters, and Northern Lights has no means by which to collect or verify a dog's history.  We work in concert with our veterinarians, and breed and age estimates are based on a combination of professional input and our collective experience.  Our policy with information acquired prior to acceptance and while the dogs are in our care is that of "full disclosure".  It is our goal to ensure the adopter has all available information to ensure the best possible match between the dog and the adopter(s).  If we have identified a behavioral or health condition while the dog is in our care and custody, every effort will be made to correct it prior to adoption, OR the adopter will be made aware of the issue or condition prior to adoption.  Northern Lights' screening process is designed to identify only those adopters who are willing, and have the means, to treat conditions which may occur after adoption, and the adopter will be contractually responsible for doing so. However, Northern Lights' policy is to accept any adopted dog back into the program, at any time, for any reason.

animal.description: Hi! Im Vlad, your best buddy to be! I hope its soon! Vlad is sort of a different name, isnt it?! The only Vlad I know of is Vlad, the Impaler. He was mean. Thats not me. I am just the opposite. Im Vlad, the Lover of People and Mighty Good Dog. Come meet me and find out yourself! Ive been around long enough 8 hooman years -- to know what peeple want from me. I am easy to walk, gentle and laid back. A shelter hooman said I am a love-bug. I even Sit for treats! I love kiddy pools, peeple petting me, and get this! BATHS! Baths feel so good, and hoomans give me lots of rubs and pets when they scrub-a-dub me. The shelter checks to see how us dogs are with peeple, food, toys, handling like a vet does, and other dogs. I did great in four out of five! This Vlad is a lover of peeple, not a lover of other dogs. I will love you so much that you wont need to share your love with any other pet. Ill greet you so happily that youll find excuses to leave home for a few minutes just so you can rush back home to my love. A crate would help me have a good start when you take me home. Its a good place for me to sleep, eat, and get treats and toys. It would be my safe place for me to blend in to my new home gradually and happily. I might have to be slowly trained to the crate, but it will help us all, a lot! Thanks for checking me out on the Internet. Now check me out in person! Fill out the adoption form. It just gathers all the information in advance for adoption to go smoother, it doesnt commit you. (I wish it did!) Ask to meet Vlad! Ill be waiting to love on you.

Sugar is a beautiful, sweet and playful 3 years old, 32 pound shepherd mix. She is looking for a family that will give her some time to settle into a home for her to call her own. Sugar needs a patient family that understands that it will take time for her to feel secure and not wanting to run. She's been working with a trainer in San Diego and has made significant process. Sugar is leash trained and crate-trained. Sugar was devastated when her previous family dumped her and sold her puppies. Sugar will need secured backyard so she has some time to adjust to her new surroundings and feel secure. She will need to be supervised in the backyard for a couple of weeks until she is bonded with her family and feels secured. 
We would suggest the new family to continue the steps that the trainer suggested, such as Crate training at night and during the day when you have to run errands. Sugar is good with other dogs that are not a threat to her. Larger dogs tend to intimate her. Sugar is food motivated which is a good sign for the key to success of continuing her training . She loves to play with soft stuffed toy toys. 

PLEASE APPLY AT OUR WEBSITE @ WWW.4DOGSFARMRESCUE.ORG

Sugar is up to date on vaccines, microchipped and spayed.

Sugar is being foster in San Diego. 

Adoption fee: $475.00

animal.description:
Benjey ACCT-A-82369

Intake Type: Owner Surrender (Aggression to Animals)
Sex: Male
Altered: No
Age: 5Y

Medical Observation:
(1/9) Normal. Mild tartar. Friendly; BAR

Behavior Observation:
(1/18) Per Foster Staff --
Kennel Presentation - Easy to leash/social. Shy but approaches kennel door and allows leashing. On return, hesitant to re-enter but will go in with a bit of encouragement, or if handler steps in first.
Leash Skills - Pulls Minimally On Leash. Walks excellently on leash with almost no pulling at all. We encountered another dog through the fence. Benjey perked his ears up and raised his tail, then trotted over to the other dog and sniffed him through the fence with tail flagging. It was very easy to redirect his attention just by calling his name, and he did not fixate on the other dog.
Handleability - Tense/Allows all handling. Was initially quite tense and took time to warm up. He was tense outside while in the run, but once he came into indoor eval room he loosened up and allowed allover handling. Eventually he began soliciting attention, licking my hand and giving kisses. He would place his head on handler's lap, lean up against handler and lay down right next to handler. He takes his time warming up, but then allows all handling and gets cuddly and affectionate. Go slow at first until he is ready.
Tag - Engages in play
Toys - Gives up willingly. Initially had Benjey in a run outside, where he was not interested in toys. He appeared tense and nervous outside and would flinch or tense up at any loud sounds or cars passing. Went into the indoor eval room, where he was still tense at first, but once he found a tennis ball he became very excited and happy, started wagging his tail and jumping around with the ball. He would drop the ball at the handler's feet and allow handler to pick it up without issue, no resource guarding observed. Very playful!
Evaluated Blue due to nervousness, but hand-shyness has improved considerably and overall behavior is much better.
(1/12) Per Foster Staff -- 
Kennel Presentation - Nervous. Nervous in kennel. Would approach handler to take treats from hand but ran away from leash. Took many attempts to successfully leash him. Once leashed, exited kennel easily. Also re-entered without issue, but then would not approach kennel door so I could remove leash. 
Leash Skills - Fearful. No pulling, but afraid of leash.
Handleability - Tense and nervous, would initially duck or move away when attempted handling. Avoidant of handler and only approached a few times for drive-by sniffs. Later approached me with some low tail wags and allowed some pets on his back, but appeared wary and whale-eyed me so handled very minimally.
Did not attempt tag. Interested in toys but does not take possession. Followed a ball when tossed. 
Evaluated Blue, recommend TTA.
(1/11) Per Foster Staff -- Attempted to remove for evaluation. Benjey would tentatively approach me to take treats but was scared of the leash and would run to the other side of the kennel any time I tried to leash him. No aggression shown, just nervous of people and afraid of leash. Will reattempt eval later today.
(1/9) Per Previous Owner -- Protects his home, obeys most of the time but can become territorial when people come to the house such as barking and trying to jump on them. He also wont allow other dogs to eat and move their bowls. He stalks around the other animals in the home and won't let them play or move around. Has been biting the other dogs in the home, usually he will stop when owner approaches and directs him to do so. Walks very nicely on leash next to his handler. Knows sit, get down, and go pee. He is a good dog but just needs the right environment without another male dog.

This animal is currently available from foster care through ACCT Philly's Adoptions Programs. This animal is not onsite. If the foster has not listed a personal email, contact foster@acctphilly.org to be put in touch with the foster. 

We encourage you to visit our shelter during our adoption hours to view our complete selection of available animals. In preparation for your visit, please make sure to visit http://www.acctphilly.org/adopt/ to review our adoption requirements, hours of operation, upcoming events, and more! 

Is this your missing pet? If you believe so, please make sure to follow the instructions listed at http://www.acctphilly.org/lostpet/ so that we can make sure that you are reunited as soon as possible!

We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Snapshot of Eloise!

Size?
Full size (35-50lbs)

Age? 9
months

Activity Level?
I play hard and snuggle hard!

Noise Level?
I like to alert people that something is happening, but I quiet down quickly!

Good with Dogs?
I'm great with slow intros!

Good with Cats?
Untested, but likely fine!

Good with Kids?
I love little ones!

Good with Strangers?
I love everyone!

Potty Trained?
I'm working on it!

Crate Trained?
I do well without one, but I like to hangout in it every once in a while.

Interested? Learn more about Eloise below!

About Eloise:

Hi! My name is Eloise! I am approximately 9 months old. I have been living with my foster dad and his three young kids who are all under the age of 10. So with that being said, I love kids! I have a lot of energy so I like that these young kids can keep up and play with me! I love to play fetch with a tennis ball. My favorite toys are ones that squeak! I'm interested in other dogs when I see them but still cautious about meeting them. I don't have any experience with cats so I'm not sure how I will handle them.

I am a good listener and already know how to sit for my treats. I'm doing very well with my potty training. I will stand by the door to let you know that I need to go outside.

I am also extremely excited to see you when you walk in the door. My tail will be going in circles and I can't wait to fill your face with kisses! If you're feeling like you just want to relax and put your feet up, then I am more than happy to cuddle up next to you and have you pet me. I will lay next to you for hours if you rub my belly!

Adoption Fee: $550

Training Requirement: Obedience Level 1 Training

*Foster to Adopt: I am looking for a forever home now, but I still need all my puppy shots and to be spayed! So I'm looking for a family that will be able to commit to bringing me to all of my appointments with TCPR until I'm ready to be fully adopted by you!

MEET ME/ADOPT ME: If you'd like to arrange a meeting or begin the adoption process, please fill out an adoption application by visiting www.twincitiespetrescue.org/adopt/adopt-a-dog/ . A volunteer from Twin Cities Pet Rescue will contact you once your application is reviewed.

FOSTER HOMES NEEDED!!! Twin Cities Pet Rescue is a volunteer-run, foster home-based organization. We can only rescue as many animals as available foster homes. Please consider saving the life of an animal in need and become a volunteer foster home today. To become a foster, fill out a dog or cat foster application on the Twin Cities Pet Rescue website: www.twincitiespetrescue.org . There is little to no cost to foster an animal. Twin Cities Pet Rescue provides its foster families with food, supplies, and veterinary care for its animals. All you need to do is supply the love!

PLEASE NOTE: Twin Cities Pet Rescue does not adopt to homes further than 60 miles from the Minneapolis/St. Paul Metro Area.
