animal.description:
Gracie
Hound Mix
1.5 years old

Gracie is a fun girl with a lot of puppy energy! She knows sit, and does well with other animals. Due to some of Gracie's puppy behaviors, she would best be suited for a family without children. Due to her vocal nature she may be better suited for a house than an apartment. 

Gracie gets overstimulated when interacting with people and gets very mouthy and grabby with hands and clothing. She will need an owner that has dog training experience and can give her consistent positive reinforcement training. 

She absolutely adores other dogs, but can be overwhelming for most dogs. She will need a very high energy playmate that can wrestle for hours if she gets placed with another dog.

We always recommend crate training, exercise, playtime, and a regular schedule for potty breaks when bringing a new dog into your home. The shelter environment is much different than your home, so expect the unexpected. We do our best to help find the right pet for you, but your new dog may act differently on your turf than he/she did on ours.  Adjustment takes time for both you and your new family member, so remember to be patient and enjoy this new and exciting time!

Included in the adoption fee are rabies (if applicable) & distemper vaccinations, heartworm testing, deworming, spay or neuter surgery.

animal.description:
If you think Ellie looks adorable in her pictures, just wait until you meet her in person!  Ellie is a 1 year old 18lb Glen of Imaal Terrier/Terrier mix who has it all - she is just the right combination of beauty and brains rolled up in one playful package. This kind and affectionate girl loves engaging with her people, whether it involves being active outside or relaxing on the couch, and relishes tummy rubs and nuzzling. She is a timid girl and needs a quiet home that will help her continue to build her confidence.

Ellie is house and crate trained, and knows her basic commands. She is highly motivated and eager to please and very, very smart. Ellie will thrive with obedience training and should easily progress to learning advanced behaviors. Her foster family tells us that she is playful with other dogs but loves attention from her people and would be fine as the only dog in the family. This sweetie has a limitless amount of love to give and will be a wonderful addition to an extremely lucky home.


Thank you so much for your interest in adopting a dog from A New Chance Animal Rescue (https://anewchancear.org). We are a 501c3, tax deductible organization. ANCAR is a foster-based rescue, and we adopt within a 90 mile radius of Bedford Hills, NY.  You will find the adoption application here: (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-application/).  All fields on the application must be completed.
Please read about the adoption process (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-process/) so you'll know what to expect when you submit.   

Our dogs are in foster care and we do NOT have a shelter or boarding facility. AN APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED IN FULL AND APPROVED BEFORE A DOG CAN BE MET. This is a firm policy. Our busy volunteers are not able to respond to questions about the dog or dog meeting requests in the absence of an application.  We know these dogs very well because they are in foster care. Please read the profiles of the dog(s) you are interested in prior to submitting an application.  If there are specific requirements stated (ie: Fenced Yard or Canine Friend Required) these are included because they are vital to the happiness, health, safety and adoption success of that dog. 

We are only able to save as many dogs as we have foster homes (https://anewchancear.org/foster/faqs/) and resources for. We provide medical care including vaccinations, testing, deworming, spaying/neutering and microchipping before transporting our dogs. We provide all supplies, preventatives and any follow up vet care necessary while they are in foster care. These costs are high and the number of lives we can save is entirely dependent upon donations from people like you.  We do not receive funding from private foundations or government sources. If you can find room in your heart to help us, with any amount, we are truly grateful (https://anewchancear.org/help/donate/). We are a 501c3 organization, so all donations are tax-deductible. It is only through the kindness of supporters like you that we are 'changing lives...one tail at a time' by providing our dogs with 'A New Chance.' (https://anewchancear.org) 

Thanks so much.

animal.description: Wilbur is a five year young beagle mix. He has longer legs and a longer snout, so we are guessing he has another hound dog mixed in there somewhere.  Don't let his looks fool you! He has greyed a bit early, probably because he had a rough life prior to rescue. We just tell him it means he's a distinguished gentleman! You see, he spent his whole life in a small little pen 24/7. Thank goodness, he was saved by animal control who knew he was not living the life he deserved. He was rescued along with his next door neighbor, a petite little beagle living in a pen next to him. Despite his less than ideal past, Wilbur has thrived in his foster home. He is a very loving boy to other dogs and every one that he meets. Don't let the grey hair fool ya, he still has plenty of giddy up and go in him! It's like he is making up for lost time. He is the perfect balance of playful and calm, not too much of either one. Wilbur loves to wrestle with his foster brother (who happens to be a young beagle), and then is also equally happy to settle down for a nap on the doggie bed. Besides playing with his foster brother, he loves to run around the back yard, nose to the ground, and talking up a storm!! It's as if he is just telling the whole world how happy he is to be free. Because of his "big hound dog voice", Wilbur is not suited for apartment life. He needs a big, fenced in yard to stretch his legs, and practice his "snout to the ground, shout it out loud" game. Wilbur is crate trained, house trained, and knows how to use a doggie door. He doesn't try to get on the furniture, but loves to curl up on the dog bed while you are watching T.V. or just hanging out. Wilbur would do best in a home with another dog that he could play and spend time with, and gets lonely (and vocal) without a buddy to hang out with. He can hardly wait to have his own home sweet home.

I was the runt of my litter and my brothers/sister are 3/4 times bigger than I am but darn if I’m not the cutest pocket pittie you’ll ever meet! My body is a little odd so my Rescue family had me in foster care until they could make sure there was nothing wrong with me medically but that was fine with me because that just means I get to spend all day playing and cuddling and those are my FAVORITE things to do!!

My foster moms says I’m a good girl but I have “puppy energy”, she told me what that was but I was too busy with one of her socks to listen!! I am potty trained but I’m not a huge fan of being outside unless someone is with me so reminders to go outside and positive encouragement are always appreciated!!

Do you have room on your couch and in your heart for my this tiny little Mouse?!

Please read entire posting for information on our new procedures. We are currently requiring appointments for all adoptions.  Please give us a call if you questions about a pet or complete an application at https://adoptmountainpets.org/pet-services/adoption-process/application-form to make arrangements to visit the Animal Resource Center.


Hi all, I'm Mesa! I came to Second Chance almost 3 months ago! I was raising my puppies but since they have all found forever homes I'm looking for my own! I get along well with other dogs but I do not like cats! I will do best in a new home with another playful confident dog.  
I am reserved lady at first and sometimes and scared of strangers.  I am hoping to find someone who can be patient with me as I learn to enjoy the world of cars, strangers, and new places.  
however, I have a heart of gold and will be loyal to end with the right BBF. 


I would do best in an active home as I have a lot of energy. Having a play mate would be pretty awesome as well! If you are interested in being my forever home please fill out an adoption application!


Adopters will be considered on the totality of the application and how it matches the particular pet's needs.


Most dogs who come from the shelter will not be house trained.

We do not know or make guarantees that a dog or cat will do well with all children, other animals or is house-trained.

We will need to talk to all of the adults in the home prior to making an appointment to visit with a pet. 

In most cases its necessary to to have family dogs come into meet your potential adoptee. Please be sure your dogs are spayed or neutered and current on vaccines (distemper - parvo and rabies) before bringing them for a meeting.

All dogs must be transported home in a travel crate to transport your new pup home safely.

Renters must provide a copy of a lease indicating pets are allowed or contact information for the landlord.


Second Chance is happy to have been providing stray, surrender, adoption, and our Community Outreach services throughout the COVID situation.   

All services are provided by appointment only.  Please do not visit the shelter without first making calling the shelter. 

For the safety of our community, staff and volunteers all visitors are required to wear masks and follow the posted social distancing processes *see below.  Do not make an appointment if you are not comfortable following these procedures.  Thank you for understanding and your support.  

If you are interested in meeting or adopting one of our pets or have questions about the process please see our website at www.adoptmountainpets.org or call the Shelter between 11:00 am and 5:45 pm Tuesday through Saturday. 970 626 2273

*  We want to provide you excellent customer service today and keep you and our team safe and healthy. Please read what we are asking you to do today to reduce the risk of spreading COVID-19:

• Maintain a distance of at least 6 feet from other people. Six feet is the average length of many dog leashes but handing a leashes to another person is not maintaining a six foot space.
• Follow staff instructions about how to drop off, pick up or meet a pet.
• If you have any symptoms of illness please reschedule.
• Wear a mask when interacting with staff
• Wash your hands or use hand sanitizer (you can find bottles throughout the property prior to interacting with staff, volunteers or pets.
• Once you have read these guidelines, please tell us you understand them and that you will follow them with at SCHS.
Thank you for your support, for adopting, for fostering and volunteering and understanding our need to do our part in stopping COVID – 19.

I love my toys and bones they’re the best as I love chewing on things, if you throw it I will go get it. I am a puppy at under 1 yea, so how can you blame me??  I’ll make a great dog park playmate if you’ve got a good arm. I need big boy toys that I can’t destroy, unless you don’t mind picking up my trail of toys that explode. ?

I’m soooo happy about everything I do, so when you say, “no”I might not get that what I did was wrong at first. I came from Korea theres a lot  to learn. I’m just a happy loving pup who is good with other dogs. I also need to be fed separately.  Since  I have been so deprived of food, I get very excited and don’t like to share. I’m a smart boy, I’m great with a bathroom routine. I’ll instantly go when you let me out and let you know when I want back in by pawing at your door in excitement.  I have had a few accidents inside since coming to America so my forever family must be committed to my potty training. 
?
I know that with the right active family who might even have a furry playmate for me and that will take the time to help me adapt and learn new things, I will shine and make an amazing forever pet.

animal.description:
Ahhh, what to say about RANDY? Home Fur Good loves this guy, and we know his perfect family is out there that will love him just the way he is. And the way Randy "is,"... is a bit special! ;-) Randy has had a few failed adoptions thus far, but we all know you don't often find true love on the first try. Randy has spent quite a bit of time with our trainer, who has helped us gain some more insight into his personality. 

To start, Randy is a FUN guy! He clearly has a talent for doggy modelling, and would love a forever home that takes lots and lots of pictures of his handsome face. Randy is always willing to pose with his "sit" and "paw" tricks, and will happily show them off for some treats. Randy has the perfect moderate energy level. Sometimes he enjoys a good run around the yard with a toy, and sometimes he's happy to curl up on a bed and chill out with a chew bone. Randy is affectionate with those he knows (he loves a good back scratch), but also independent enough to sniff around and explore on his own. In fact, Randy has quite the independent streak to him, which is part of what has made finding his perfect forever fit a bit of a challenge. Per Home Fur Good's trainer, Randy has quite a stubborn streak to him, and will do best in a home that sets boundaries while still allowing Randy to be Randy. He does not enjoy being "forced" to do things, and does not respond well to "discipline-based" dog training. Randy will do best in a home that loves him just the way he is, and is willing to get to know Randy on his terms. Randy will also do best in a home with no small children, and no other animals. 

We KNOW Randy's perfect person is out there waiting for him... could that person be YOU? Randy is listed at three years old and weighs 52 pounds. Randy is currently in board and train with Home Fur Good's trainer in Phx. Call 602-971-1334 and we will get you in touch with Randy's trainer for a meet and greet. Randy's adoption fee is $150 and includes prior training, spaying/neutering, age-appropriate vaccinations, microchipping, and a free wellness visit at Phoenix Mountain Animal Hospital. Our adoption hours are Thursday-Saturday from 11:00 am-4:00 pm by appointment only.

animal.description:
This adorable duo is officially in search of their forever home. Chico and Rico are a pair of bonded chihuahuas and looking for a home together. While we don't know their entire background, we do know that they were found wandering the streets of Texas together. Both boys were rescued and found to be heartworm positive. After undergoing treatment, they made the long trek north in search of a loving home. 

Rico is 2 years old and weighs 10lbs. He is very outgoing and friendly. He enjoys playing, snuggling and giving lots of kisses. He loves his crate and is almost completely potty trained to go outside, although he is still working on it and has the occasional accident indoors. 

Chico is 2 years old and weighs 5lbs. He is a little more timid, but once he warms up he loves a good snuggle session and giving lots of kisses. He likes his kennel and is trained to use potty pads. He will go outside to go potty as well, but has not yet adjusted to the cold Wisconsin winter. Chico tends to be more nervous and prefers a calm and quiet atmosphere so a home with no small children would be best. 
Chico and Rico are adjusting well to living indoors but will need patience while they continue to adjust to the chilly weather in Wisconsin. If you are looking for someone to keep you warm on those long, cold winter nights, then these little lap warmers just might be the perfect match for you!


If you are already pre-approved or have any questions about Chico and Rico please email our adoptions team at misfitmuttsdogrescue@gmail.com. If you are interested in adopting this bonded pair please head over to misfitmuttsdogrescue.com and fill out an adoption application.

animal.description:
*Adoption Process starts with an Online Adoption Application you can find at www.adoptaboston.com.  Phone interviews do not take place til after an approved application is on file.

Eligible for the Golden Paws Program (adoptors 60 yrs and older adopting a dog 7 yrs and older get $50 off the adoption fee noted below)

My name is Molly. I am a 9 year old CORGI MIX (no boston in me, sorry) and weigh 27 pounds. I need a new home because my owner needs surgery and can't take care of me no longer.  I am being fostered in Des Moines, IA.
 
I love squeaky toys
I have lots of energy.  I need playtime and walks.
I would rather not any other pets in my home. I have a history of starting fights.
I need tummy rubs, kisses and lots of treats.
I enjoy the humans in the house, pets from them and being able to do tricks for them but not much of a cuddle bug..  I do not always want to sleep in bed with my humans.

Remember that age is just a number. I act like a puppy.  I can self entertain when needed.  I love to run around the fence line and chase squirrels but also relax watching through the window.
 
Here's a little more about me:
Housetrained?  Yes
Leash-trained?  Yes
Rides well in car?  Yes, love!!!
Good with other dogs? No, I lived with other dogs and not a fan. I would be the one to start the fights.
Good with cats? No
Good with young children? Prefer a low active household so no young children.
Good with strangers?  Yes but need time to trust especially with men but I will come around
Shy or confident?  confident
Barks?  at squirrels
Apartment qualified?  No, I want a fenced in yard to run in
Any Special needs or Health Issues?  None
Adoption fee: $125

All our dogs are spayed/neutered (if six months and older), up to date on rabies and distemper, heartworm tested, and microchipped. Other medical needs diagnosed while in foster care are also treated prior to adoption.

MABTR requires a fenced in area from families who own their home, however we DO adopt to apartment complexes and communities where fences are not permitted due to leases and covenants. In these cases a leash law must be enforced.  We do not accept invisible fencing.

MABTR only adopts to families residing in NE, CO, MO, KS, IA, WY, SD, ND, ID, UT, MT, MN, and SW corner of AR due to the lack of volunteer support in other states, no exception even if you are willing to drive.

If you are Interested in Adoption please complete our online adoption application at https://www.adoptaboston.com/adopt/application/. Petfinder's form is NOT our application.  We will respond back to you within 72 hours of receiving your application.

Interested in Donating visit https://www.adoptaboston.com/help/

Hi, my name is Stella! Here is what would work best for me in my new home:

-Personality: Friendly, playful, loves people
-Can Live with Kids: Yes, respectful kids of any age
-Can Live with Cats: Unknown history - will need slow proper introduction to ensure everyone gets along
-Can Live with Dogs: Yes, after an initial introduction here at the shelter and a prolonged introduction process in the home. No rude or rowdy dogs, PLEASE - I am a senior lady and have no interest in being tormented.
-Can do Apartment Living: Yes, with plenty of exercise and mental stimulation
-Potty Trained: It appears so
-Bite History: No
-Positive Reward Based Obedience Classes Required: Yes, one private lesson (due to breed)
-Energy Level: Medium
-Needs Medical Procedure Before Going Home: No
-Additional Information: Stella is an older gal looking for a nice, low-key home to spend the rest of her days! She was surrendered to us for frequently escaping her previous home, so she should never be left unattended outside. As a senior dog, Miss Stella will need more frequent vet check-ups to ensure that she is happy and healthy. If this sweet girl sounds like a good match for your home, make sure to head up front and fill out an application with customer service!

Copy and paste the link to access the sign-up genius for an appointment: https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet for dogs and https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1 for cats.

For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time. 

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to elenahtar@gmail.com

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE:
http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Raye was found as a stray along with her brother and sister. She is very sweet and loving but very timid. Raye has been with her foster family, which includes adults, children and dogs, for about 2 months getting ready for her forever home. They have made her feel loved and shown her what it is like to have a family. She was very scared initially and has improved but takes a while to warm up to people. Once she does, she willingly approaches for pets and likes to hang out with her people on the couch. She takes a little longer to feel comfortable with children but is getting there and is gentle. She will do best in a home with another dog to help her build confidence. She does ok on a leash and enjoys going outside. Raye is looking for a loving, patient adopter who can continue to help her gain the confidence to become the wonderful dog that she is.

Adoption Coordinator: Elena
Location: Foster Home

The adoption fee for this dog is $475. This fee INCLUDES spay/neuter and microchip. 

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description:
PLEASE read bio in full!!!!

Thank you for your interest in adoption from Palmetto Paws. If you would like to be considered to adopt from PPAR please complete the online application on the home page. Completing an application does not guarantee an adoption. The age to be considered for adoption is 21.

We will not consider applications for those not able to meet/adopt on the next upcoming Saturday or at a time designated by the rescue. Adoptions are done usually on Saturdays as we are all volunteers who work full time during the week. Dogs live in private foster homes. We do not host events and there is no opportunity to view multiple dogs. 
We will not consider incomplete applications. We will not process applications that are not for a specific dog listed on petfinder. We do not process and "hold" applications. We do not ship dogs and we do not arrange transports. All adopters must be present to complete the adoption. If an adopter is approved we do a “meet and greet” with a specific dog or pup. If at the meet we all agree it’s a good match, then the adoption takes place at that time. Their is no opportunity to meet and adopt at a later date. Again, please only apply if you are available on Saturday and ready to adopt.

Please keep in mind that we do our best to make an educated guess as to the breeds of our rescued pets. In rescue we rarely see the parents puppies, and even when we do, they are usually mixed breeds as well. We will never promise a particular breed or adult size.

We do our best to put all info we have in the bio. We will not respond to inquires regarding information that is already detailed in the bio. 

My name is Cricket . I am about 10 years old and I weigh around 10 pounds. I was being given away on a swap page on Thanksgiving 2020. I was so matted that you could not even see my face. I had to be shaved by the groomer and then my beautiful face was revealed, as were my blinding cataracts. I was taken to Dr Fischer at Animal Eye Care of the Lowcounty and long story short I have new lenses and now have perfect vision. I have had two follow up appointments and all went fantastic. I will need an adopter who will continue to be able to take me to future appointments with the specialist and continue needed eye drops. The adopter will cover the cost of all future visits and medications so if that is not something you are willing to do then please do not apply. 
Cricket has also been seen by our Vet and had a complete senior blood panel done, spay and dental. As she is a senior and already has medical needs please think about this prior to applying- seniors need to see the Vet more frequently, and develop medical issues just as us older humans do.

Cricket resides in a home with dogs, cats and a toddler. She tolerates them all just fine but a full-time toddler is not what Cricket would prefer. She is very good with Charlotte but doesn't want the full-time attention of a small child. Cricket is fine with the cats and good with the large dogs in the home. We feel cricket would do fine with or without other dogs as long as the other dogs are not constantly wanting to play as she is not interested.
Cricket would prefer to be in your lap or held at all times (as many littles do).  She is very sweet and loving. She has had no accidents since early intake. She is decent on leash and rides well in the car. She even went on vacation with her foster family and did great!

All adopters are provided with a medical summary, a new collar and leash, an opportunity to go over basic training/pet care and help shopping for supplies if needed. 

 The adoption fee is $425 .

If interested in adoption please submit an application! The application is found on our home page at palmettopaws.petfinder.com

animal.description:
**Please note that a bite waiver will be required as part of Anthony’s adoption.

Please give a warm S.N.O.R.T. welcome to Anthony. This five-year-old, 24 lb, boy came to us after his owner passed away.

This sweet little boy loves nothing more than to cuddle and relax on the couch. He's a bit shy, so it will take him some time to warm up. But all good things to come to those who wait because once he's comfortable, he'll be all over you! In typical Velcro Frenchie fashion, Anthony will drape himself across your lap and sneak in some kisses. His tongue doesn't quite fit in his mouth, so be ready for a kiss attack! A quirk of his is to sit straight up on his bottom when he'd like some belly rubs.

Anthony isn't so energetic and would be fine with a daily walk. Even though he's a couch potato, he enjoys playtime. He loves small soft balls. He would love it if you threw a ball to him so that he can hit it back to you with his nose. Once he's done playing, it's cuddle time! You can level up your cuddling, with Anthony, by letting him under the covers so he can curl up against you.

He is a smart boy but can be a little mischievous! His future family will have to establish themselves as the pack leader due to his dominant personality. Anthony has also been known to be a performer. He'll show off his tricks of sit, sit pretty and stay. He is a bulldog though, so he may not always want to. Part of this may be due to the fact that his hearing isn't the best.

Anthony gets anxious around new people, places and busy settings. If strangers approach him, he will try and lunge at them or try to bite someone trying to pet him. Anthony's foster home has found some techniques to help with introducing him to new people, which they'll teach his new family.

Anthony will do best in a laid back home with someone that has experience with the bully breeds. The ideal home for Anthony is with adults only. Anthony prefers women, but we think he would do fine with a man as long as they're patient and give him space. In the past, he bit two men who did not respect his space, even though they were asked to. Due to his fear of strangers, Anthony would not do well in a city or busy area. We feel he would do better in the suburbs or a rural area in a single family home.

Due to his anxiety, Anthony wouldn't be a fit to go to work or be home all day by himself.

Anthony's future home should not have other dogs or cats due to his high prey drive. He is territorial of his home and becomes overstimulated easily, which can cause him to lash out. His energy can be unappealing to some dogs because when he gets anxious, it's hard for him to settle down.

Like most Frenchies, Anthony has allergies and needs to avoid chicken, turkey and beef. To help with his itchiness, Anthony takes an allergy supplement and gets a monthly medicated bath. A fish supplement could also help keep the itchies at bay. In his arsenal of tricks, Anthony knows "no feeties" to stop licking his paws. He will also need to have his anal glands expressed regularly. 

Anthony is very loyal and thrives when he is with his people at home. If you think you are his new best friend, submit a S.N.O.R.T. adoption application today! His fee is $500.

Please submit an adoption application on our website!  https://www.snortrescue.org/adoption-process/adoption-application/

Note: All dogs in SNORT's care are fostered in private homes by  dedicated volunteers. SNORT's adoption fee includes appropriate veterinary care, all necessary vaccines, and a spay/neuter. SNORT posts regular updates about our foster dogs on our Facebook page,  http://www.facebook.com/pages/SNORT-Short-Noses-Only-Rescue-Team/128712140542769.  Like us on Facebook for the latest news on our dogs, fundraisers, and rescue  efforts!

animal.description:
Hi there. These cuties are the Roman Gods and Goddesses litter. They were born approximately 12/02, so they're currently 8 weeks old. We aren't quite sure what breed mix they are. We believe that Mom (Mathilda) is a Labrador Retriever, possibly with some pit or terrier DNA. We don't know who the pups' dad is, but based on the puppies' looks and build, dad might have been a hound dog, possibly a pointer. Whatever breed mix they are, they are happy, healthy puppies. And they are lucky puppies. Their entire pack were stays, and a concerned citizen who had been feeding the pack and had been working to gain their trust called Animal Control for help. AC picked up Mathilda, the puppies and an older sibling. So the puppies have been in foster care about four weeks, and they are friendly, social puppies. They love everyone, and they enjoy being held. They love to run and play. They love toys. They love going for walks in the woods with their foster mom's pack - dogs and goats. They're just a bunch of happy puppies - they love everything! But what they'd really love most of all is a family of their own. Could that be you? The pups are being fostered in Eatonton, and they'll be ready to go home with their furever families next week.

All of these puppies will be totally vetted - up to date on vaccines, worming, heartworm preventative, microchipped and spayed / neutered. They're still just young pups though, so they have yet to learn about house training and obedience training. 

If you are interested in giving one of the Gods and Goddesses puppies a forever home, please visit the link below to fill out an application! http://fureverafterrescue.org/adoption-application.html. It is best to submit an application through a computer. We have experienced some problems when applications have been submitted using a mobile device. When you submit the application, you are not obligated to adopt; however, it does reserve for you the opportunity to adopt that particular animal. Please note that several of the puppies have already been pre-adopted. We currently have one little girl (Nona) and three of the boys available.

Before submitting an application, please make sure your references (landlord, personal and veterinary) are aware that you are looking to adopt a pet and that we may be calling for a reference. Please note, our volunteers may call from other than a Georgia area code. If we are unable to reach your references, the person calling will leave a voice mail, if it is set up on the phone. If personal references fail to call us back, the application remains in a pending status and cannot be processed further. Please allow up to a week, or more in some cases, for us to process your application, we are primarily a volunteer organization and at certain times can receive very high volumes of applications and emails.

If your application is approved, we will contact you to proceed with the adoption process. If you choose not to adopt, we will contact the next approved applicant. If you have any questions or difficulties, please contact us, we will be glad to help!

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Garrison. I am a blue/grey bully mix, a large teddy bear. At 70+ pounds, I'm actually pretty gentle! With my short snout and one ear that stands up, I've been melting the hearts of all who meet me. 
How do I behave? I am a great companion. At approximately 5 years old, I love to run, play, fetch and then chill out and lay around. I am crate trained and house trained I am eager to please, smart, and learn fast. I sit perfectly for your attention and for treats. I would be best behaved and happiest with exercise and rules. 
How social am I? Well I am kind and easy going. Trusting and loving, I enjoy my people and I like when strangers say hello, too! I am great on car rides, but need more training on walks. So far, I've played well with other dogs. I just want to play! My people have observed me taking correction well from my canine friends. I have not been tested with cats or other small animals, but I definitely notice them from a distance and have a prey drive. 
I feel pretty good! I have experienced some intestinal issues, but am feeling much better. I must maintain my excellent nutritional diet! It is good for my skin type, too A weird thing: I was trying to eat my own feces! I've been improving, but sometimes am still tempted. That will need continued attention so that I can stay healthy and strong. 

If you'd like to know more about me, let us know! 
Woof, 
Garrison Primary Color: Blue Secondary Color: White Weight: 69lbs Age: 5yrs 2mths 2wks Animal has been Neutered

animal.description:
Tell you about Cordy, you say?
 
We'd love to.
 
Cordy is a very special dog who has not had an easy life. Cordy (and her friend Boots) came from a hoarding case and never got the socialization that puppies so desperately need. So nowCordy has a lot of catching up to do, and we have stepped in to help her do just that! It's the "Teach Cordy how to do real dog stuff" team.
 
We are slowly watching joy seep its way out of Cordy. First tail wags, first zoomies, first "oh my god that feels so good" wiggles during a solid butt scratch. Patience is key with Cordy, but we are slowly seeing some of the milestones we have been waiting for. Cordy needs extremely patient humans who understand that she has a long way to go, but are willing to put in the time and reap the rewards. Fast movements, loud sounds and new things are all very scary to her and she will need time to learn these things will not hurt her. She is not leash trained and still panics when she reaches the end of the leash, but we are taking time in getting her comfortable with the feeling. She is great at keeping her space clean and knows that outside time is potty time.
 
One thing that seems to build Cordy's confidence is having a confident dog friend around. Cordy takes her time getting comfortable around dog friends (a lot of time) and needs a canine friend who is willing to go at her pace. But a confident friend can go a long way to teach this special girl how to do real dog stuff. Cordy is seeking an adult only home with a dog friend and no kitties. Cordy would gladly go home with her friend Boots who came from the same background, but can go home without her as well. We are requiring a fenced in yard for Cordy as she is not leash trained and can panic at times, and this would be the safest option for her.
 
If you are interested in Cordy, have lots of patience, a securely fenced in yard and a dog looking for a buddy (or a student of life?), please call the shelter at 603-472-3647 to speak with an adoption counselor.

animal.description:
This is our friend Boots.
 
Boots is a very, very unique lady with a lot of learning to do. Boots (and her pal Cordy) came from a hoarding situation where she did not get the socialization that puppies so desperately need. So, she has a lot of catching up to do to learn how to be a "real dog". A lot of things are new to her. Being touched, being pet, playing, all dog stuff really. But us staff are dedicated to find the joyful dog we know is inside her.
 
Boots will need a lot of time, a lot of patience, and a lot of love. We are still working on finding the things that bring Boots enough joy to break down her walls. She is a lady who likes to be on the move. Once she is on a leash she enjoys walking around and this is when we see the most excitement in her. When things are still, Boots has too much time to think and her walls go back up. She has spent more time with one of our staff than the others and has shown that she can develop a relationship and a bond, but her bond still looks quite different than the normal dog's human-animal bond. We do not think that the shelter is the right environment to break Boots' walls down, but we are doing everything we can despite. We believe Boots' will make more progress in a quiet home with more consistency and a routine, and lots of love.
 
Because Boots is not leash trained, we do require a fenced in yard for her. Boots can live with other dogs, however she does not appear to have a whole lot of interest in them, so she will need a dog who will give her space as she is not interested in playing at this point in her life. Super playful dogs seeking a BFF will not find that in Boots. She is seeking an adult only home without cats. Boots certainly could go home with her friend Cordy, but it is not a necessity.
 
If you are interested in Boots please call the shelter at 603-472-3647 to speak with an adoption counselor.

animal.description:
Dash is a handsome 9-year-old male Shih Tzu that weighs 14 pounds. He is the sweetest little guy that will make the perfect companion for anyone! He loves exploring the backyard, playing with other dogs, doesn't mind cats, and is very social. He has never met a stranger! He does great with kids and really loves when they play with him. Dash has dry eye, which is very common in Shih Tzu's, but inexpensive lubricating eye drops fix that up! He is neutered, vaccinated, heartworm negative, microchipped, and recently had a dental. He is $350 plus TX sales tax with an approved application: www.recycledpomsbcs.com/adopt

Texas law requires that all humane organizations (Rescues, SPCA's, Humane Societies, State nonprofit, and charitable 501c3 exempt orgs) collect and remit sales and use tax to the Texas Comptroller on their adoption fees.

We do not ship or transport our dogs. We require all adopters to meet the dog in person to ensure it is a good fit. We represent the dog to the best of our ability and since they are in rescue, we do not always get their history.

Please note: We are a non-profit Pomeranian Rescue with dogs in private foster homes. We do not have a facility open to the public. We require an approved application before a potential adopter is introduced to a dog. We contact vet references to ensure animals in the home are current on vaccinations, heart worm prevention, and sterilization. We do not adopt our dogs to homes in which an animal is not spayed or neutered. A home visit may be required.

Please visit our website for more information and an adoption application. www.recycledpomsbcs.com

animal.description:
Sermon is a 3 year old American Staffordshire Terrier mix, who weighs about 65 lbs. He came to us from a rural shelter in Ohio and has enjoyed being spoiled in his foster home! He's very sweet, especially loves his foster dad, and is starting to figure out chew toys. He's getting along great with his canine foster sister and is still in the process of sweet-talking his feline foster sister into cohabitating peacefully!

Sermon is fully potty trained and is close to perfecting his crate training. He is great in his crate at night, but is a bit whiney during the workday. He will lay quietly on his bed for an entire workday, as long as he can be close to his humans. All in all, he's a pretty lazy pup but will play in spurts and would benefit from daily walks to try to get a few pounds off of him!

He has been neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, and is heartworm negative. His adoption fee is $300. If you are interested in adopting Sermon, please apply on our website, www.prodogshio.org/adoptables.

He's being fostered in the Cincinnati area. Please note, we only schedule meet and greets with approved applicants. We are not currently hosting adoption events due to Covid.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
We appreciate your support, in order to help us continue to rescue dogs! Donations can be made via our PayPal account - info@prodogsohio.org.
You must be willing to commute to the location that the pet is being fostered in order to be eligible to adopt. We do not ship our pets. We also require that you personally bring the pet back to us should the adoption not work out.
We do NOT negotiate adoption fees. All money goes to support our rescue operation. We are 100% volunteered based.
We require your current dog(s) to be current on vaccines and heartworm prevention.
Apply online at www.prodogsohio.org, under the Adoptables tab.
Due to the volume of apps and inquiries, we may not be able to respond to everyone.

animal.description:
***URGENT - Chester needs an adoptive or foster home by Jan. 31st, 2021. Please thoroughly read through is bio below to see if you are able to help Chester.***

**Due to Chester's behavioural needs please submit a application first at www.rapsbc.com. Management will review applications and set up meet and greets for suitable applicants only. Please call us at 604-275-2036 if you have any questions.**

PERSONALITY: Meet Chester - our very handsome but also rather complex fellow.

Chester suffers from anxiety, is under socialized and can be fearful - especially with new places, people and dogs. Because of this he is fear reactive to both people and dogs. Chester is also affected by environmental stimulus and can quickly reach and go over his thresholds. Therefore, Chester requires to always wear a muzzle when out for walks and other excursions - his new parents or family must be comfortable with this.

Being in the Shelter causes Chester quite a bit of stress and which causes him to act out more often due to his anxiety - he is currently on medication to help with this anxiety. We have also come to learn that he has barrier reactivity. When Chester is in these heightened states he will sometimes redirect - he has put his mouth on many of the kennel attendants.

Chester was being fostered by our Assistant Manager for a few months and did quite well, though still reactive in certain situations to new people or dogs. Chester was a loveable, silly boy in his foster home and enjoyed having zoomies in the yard and playing with toys, so we know he has the potential to be a good boy - he just needs the right family to come along. We also had our trainer work with Chester and he did quite well and was able to hang out with some of her dogs when introduced properly.

Chester needs a calm household with no other animals and no children. He requires calm, confident handlers that are willing to work with him on his behavioural needs as well as ongoing socialization. Chester is also not fully house trained so will need someone that can positively help him learn this. Having Chester in your life will require a lifestyle adjustment but he is definitely worth it.

Lastly, due to Chester's breeds - we believe Wheaten Terrier/Poodle - he needs regular grooming.

LIKES: Zoomies and Playtime

DISLIKES: New Situations

AGE: Approximately 2 years & 10 months

If you are interested in Chester, you can call our shelter at 604-275-2036, or email us at info@rapsbc.com.

Molly is a pure bred Female Golden Retriever who was born and raised in Turkey!. She is one of 38 beautiful Golden Retrievers who have been rescued from the harsh conditions animals must endure in that country and has been living in her present US home for three years.  As you can see, she is a lovely five year old English Cream Golden Retriever who is quite the joy to her present family but sadly, due to a recent divorce, the Mom feels she is overwhelmed with a full time job, two young boys, two dogs and a home so she is making the very difficult choice to surrender Molly and her "brother" back to GREAT Rescue.

Gary is the little boy who always has a stuffed toy in his mouth. He is a little smaller than Molly, is 2 1/2 years old and also came to GREAT Rescue after being rescued at 8 weeks of age from a local animal shelter along with his two sisters and brother.  Lucky for that sweet and gentle boy to be adopted into a home where he could enjoy the love of a wonderful family, two boys and, of course, of his new friend and mentor, Molly. Gary is believed to be a Lab mix with a truly "Golden Retriever" heart!

Molly and Gary are both excellent in the house although Gary is crated when no one is home and they ride well in the car. They have had professional training at Jet Set which has also offered a refresher session to their new family.  Molly is more of a Mama's girl while Gary loves everyone.  They love to wrestle and play with each other, go to the dog park and take long walks daily.

Both are in excellent health- they are heartworm negative, spayed/neutered, current on all vaccinations, wormed, chipped and looking for their new forever home.  THEIR NEW HOME MUST BE IN THE JACKSONVILLE, FLORIDA AREA, HAVE A FENCED YARD, A FAMILY MEMBER WHO WILL WALK THEM DAILY, NO OTHER PETS AND SOMEONE WHO IS HOME MUCH OF THE TIME.  THEY WILL NOT BE SEPARATED.  

We are seeking a Foster to Adopt home for Molly and Gary.  If you are interested in making Molly and Gary part of your family, go to greatresscue.org to complete/submit a foster application or wait until tomorrow for the new adoption application to be posted.  For additional information, please contact greatrescue@comcast.net or 501-6899.

IMPORTANT!!!!! FOREVER HOME MUST HAVE A FRIENDLY, YOUNG,

PLAYFUL AND CONFIDENT RESIDENT DOG OR TWO!

MEET BUTTERCUP, a beautiful, 18 month old and 45lb lab mix who recently found herself in a terribly precarious situation. Poor little BUTTERCUP was lost alone and frightened, running with cows in a pasture while being shot at by the farmer. She's a very lucky girl, as she did avoid getting shot long enough for a good samaritan to get her to safety.

She is currently in an awesome foster home and her foster momma shares: "Buttercup is doing great. All is going wonderfully! She is such a sweet sweet girl. She was a little shy in the beginning, but warmed up quickly. She is learning so much from having two brothers. She is still settling into her foster home, learning to just relax and lay down when my resident dogs do. She loves to play and is great with toys. She's a smart girl and highly treat and praise motivated. She is getting used to the crate, plays wonderfully with the boys and no accidents in the house. Buttercup is a champion cuddle bug and enjoys lots of pets and love!" More soon so dog-ear Buttercup's page and come back soon.

BUTTERCUP is spayed and up to date on age-appropriate vaccines. Her adoption fee is $425. Please note that training is highly recommended for all dogs. As with all rescue animals, breed determination cannot be validated without genetic testing.

THANKS FOR ADOPTING AND SAVING A LIFE; you are BUTTERCUP'S hero!

animal.description:
Meet Rosie! This purebred American Basset Hound has been fully vetted after being discarded by her owner in TJ. Rosie is spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed and negative for ehrlichia and other common diseases.

Rosie is very dog friendly and will need some help with her potty training for the lack of consistent training.

If you are not familiar with the breed please research the breed attributes before applying, Basset Hounds are great family dogs and can be stubborn and vocal at some times, even with they easy going personality.

PLEASE NOTE: Breed mix info is the best guess of ScratchMyBelly and our vets. There is no way to know for certain what any dog's breed mix is without a DNA test.

Homes with doggie doors will not be approved, sorry we are seeing a lot of problems with unsupervised animals and wild life.

We require a Home Check to set you & our Dog up for a successful transition into his/her furever home. This is only about the safety of the dog & in no way a judgement of you or your home. Our contract states that should you not want our Dog for ANY reason we will happily take our Dog back into our Rescue.

*WE NEED AN ADOPTION APPLICATION TO START THE PROCESS*

1. Submit Application
Go to our website www.scratchmybelly.org/forms. Your application is not a guarantee of placement, our process is not first come, first serve and we have the right to refuse the application. If you “rent” please make sure you check with your Landlord you can have a pet prior to submitting your application, many landlords have weight and/or breed restrictions.

2. Interview
We endeavor to make sure we are matching you with the right dog so a phone interview helps to insure we are all on the same page.

3. Meet the Pet
We can Meet n Greet at Home Check or you meet the foster. Every situation is different. We try to accommodate each on a personal level.

4. Home Check
We check for safety for the dog. We know our dogs well & can spot a potential problem quickly. We also call this a meet n greet.

5. Sign Adoption Contract
Contracts are signed the day of adoption, we accept PayPal to the Rescue Group & the Dog goes to his new home.

Due to the hundreds of inquires we cannot guarantee anything. ALL THE APPLICATIONS ARE SENT TO THE FOSTER FOR REVIEW.   IF THE FOSTER CHOOSES YOUR HOME FOR A PUPPY, SHE WILL "CALL YOU" WITHIN FIVE DAYS OF RECEIVING YOUR APPLICATION.   OTHERWISE, YOU WILL NOT HEAR FROM THE FOSTER.

It does not help us if you are sending us multiple emails, texts and calls. 
We are a volunteer based rescue organization.

animal.description:
"Big Silly Pyr" Meet handsome Bain, a big goofy Pyr born around January 2020. Still, very much a puppy, weighing 75 lbs, he was rescued by the Great Pyrenees Rescue Society from a Texas animal shelter as a stray.

Bain is sociable and gets along with everyone, and has some basic training. He requires a resident canine companion to show him the ropes and help him settle into his new home. A big securely fenced yard to run and play would keep Bain exercised and safe.

He would do well in an active home with older, considerate kids. He is a fun, bright Pyr and needs assured leaders in his family familiar with Pyr characteristics and habits. Please complete an Adoption Application if Bain would fit perfectly with your family.

PUPPIES ARE ONLY PLACED IN HOMES WITH YOUTHFUL, PLAYFUL RESIDENT DOGS.

Our requirements for puppy adoption are simple and necessary.

Our puppies are not livestock guardians, they are family pets that live inside the family home.

Puppies must be placed in homes with a youthful, adult resident dog of similar size. This gives the puppy a mentor and a solid foundation for becoming part of the family.

Puppies are only adopted to homes with someone at home at least part of the day. If no one is home for 6-8 hours at a time, please do not apply.

Preference is always given to those with Great Pyrenees experience.

Applicants must have secure, visible fencing and a socialization plan in place.

The fastest way to be considered for a puppy is to fill out an application. Adoption is not first come, first served. GPRS and its fosters work diligently to find the right fit for each and every unique dog and puppy.

Adoption Fee $450 (Adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm test, rabies, distemper, parvo and health certificate for travel). Northwest adopters pay the cost of transport to independent transport service ($225). Adoption applications can be found on our website at https://www.greatpyreneesrescuesociety.org.

ADOPTION, FOSTERING, AND DONATIONS are just some of the ways you can help a rescued dog. We have worked hard to cultivate a large network of volunteers to save this majestic breed. While monetary donations are always much appreciated, you can also help by donating your time as a GPRS foster or volunteer!

Hi, I'm Lana. I'm 4 years old and just your typical shepherd! I'm a super smart, outgoing and energetic girl.The people here say I'm a genius! I know sit, paw, down and we are working on lie down! I love to keep busy with puzzles and toys. I'd love a home with people who are active and outdoorsy, so I can go on long walks and adventures! I am already leash-trained and house-trained! After a long day of exercise and play, I love cuddle time. I love all people and would like to be the center of your world. I may have a bit too much energy for small children, but I still love them! My last owners recently got another dog and brought me here because I didn't get along with him. I want to be your one and only pet, I love affection! I don't mind seeing well-behaved dogs, but I prefer them at a distance. I love to play, cuddle, and learn new things! I can be talkative and may bother your neighbors if you live in an apartment or townhouse, so a single family home with a yard (especially if it's fenced in!) is where I would do best. I can't wait to meet you; I hope you love me as much as I'll love you! A generous donor has sponsored my adoption fee! That means approved adopters can take me home for $0 and use that money to spoil me with Christmas gifts!

DISCLAIMER: Lana MUST be in the only pet in a home. She cannot live with cats, dogs, or other small animals. 

If interested in adoption, please submit an online adoption application. After we process your application, we will contact you to schedule an appointment! Due to COVID-19, all animal meetings must be scheduled by appointment, only after we have received and reviewed your application. Thank you!

animal.description:
Rango is a happy, affectionate, energetic 63 pound boy who arrived at the shelter in somewhat tragic circumstances.  He bit his owner over food; but apparently he was also beaten with a spatula several times.

Since he has been at the shelter, Rango has learned to trust people again and enjoys playing ball and going for walks.  His leash manners are excellent, and he willingly trades his tennis balls when asked.  At this point, he is working on his food bowl issues, and he is looking for an owner that understands behavior modification practices.

The shelter's trainer is willing to work with prospective adopters who want to give this boy a second chance for a happy and secure life.

Due to Covid, the shelter is has an appointment only policy. We ask potential adopters to fill out our application, prior to a scheduled meeting. The staff is very accommodating, and we welcome any inquires.

animal.description:
Sweet Molly is 4 years old. She is very affectionate, happy and playful. She greets people she trusts with her legs wiggling in the air for a belly rub. She is an adorable dog with a crazy under bite that gives her a unique look.

Molly is food aggressive, therefore she needs a consistent, experienced owner committed to continuing a behavior plan. The shelter will pro-active in her training. The shelter has been working with Molly using positive training and she is responding very well. In fact, Molly is learning many excellent behaviors including walking well on the leash, waiting for treats and the food bowl, sitting, coming when called (here) and stay. She does an awesome high five for a treat. 

Although Molly lived with a family consisting of children, 2 cats (which frightened her by bopping her with their paws), and another dog, we feel she is best suited to a quiet adult household.

Due to Covid, the shelter is has an appointment only policy. We ask potential adopters to fill out our application, prior to a scheduled meeting. The staff is very accommodating, and we welcome any inquires.

This link will take you to our adoption application.
https://capemaycountynj.gov/DocumentCenter/View/5814/Adoption-Application

animal.description:
Name: Trouble
Sex: Male  
Color: Black and White
Age: 10 - 12
Approx Weight:  15 lbs
ID number:  OH 1357
Good w/dogs: No
Good w/cats: Yes
Crate Trained: Other - see description
Housebroken:  Yes
Energy Level:  Moderate
Health: Will need 1 - 3 teeth removed and teeth cleaning
Good w/Kids:  Yes if 13 yrs old or older
Training:  Come, sit, stay
Fostered In:  Ohio
My Adoption Donation:  $250

More Info:  Hi! My name is Trouble but, don't let that worry you because I'm a very good boy. My foster mom and dad say I'm no trouble at all. I am 10-12 year old so I'm a pro at telling you when I need to go out. I like lots of love, petting and enjoy napping during the day. I love to nestle under blankets and be close to my foster mom. If you're looking for your shadow then I'm your man. I will need to be with someone who is home most of the time because I have separation anxiety and enjoy the company of my people. I like walks and sniffing along the way and do well on my leash. I'm not a big fan of the snow or rain but, I will go outside to do my business quickly. I have 3 cat foster siblings and I like them. Sometimes I follow them when they leave the room and they don't always like that so I return to where I was sitting. 
The only thing I ask is that you not sneak up on me because I get startled. I don't chew on things that aren't mine and I take good care of my toys. My cheetah bear is my favorite and I like to carry him around. I like to play a quick game of fetch before I go to bed and then I crawl under a blanket for the night. My foster mom says I'm the best boy ever.

(Added  )

Application, veterinary reference, adoption fee and home check required to adopt. APPLY TO ADOPT VIA our link: http://midwestbtrescue.org/

NOTE: Please do not email for more dog info. This is all the info available until approved and then you can talk directly to that dogs foster home for further info. Thank you!

She will only be adopted into a sport-dog home! 

She will excel at disc, trick training, agility, flyball, herding, barn hunt, lure coursing, dock diving, etc. 

Her favorite activity is fetch, she is extremely fast, and will play with you all day long! 

Nitro is one of our star students at our training program through @woofgangrehab and @shadesofbludogtraining 

She is skilled in advanced obedience training, trick training, socialization, crate training, and more. 

Nitro moved through her training program at Nitro speed (LOL) and has WOWed our trainers with her extreme intelligence, loyalty, willingness to please, and confidence! 

She is currently in her foster home with one of our trainers, @doggietraux.

Nitro is working on her slight discomfort around children, and we have been facilitating bonds between her and young children through training sessions. She would do best in a home without children or with children that will be considerate of her space and be gentle with her. 

She loves to play with other dogs! 
 

She is available for meet and greets and adoption at this time!



To apply for your new best friend, please fill out our online application!

animal.description:
7 1/2 years old.  45lbs.  JJ made his way up to us from TN where he was pulled from an overcrowded shelter.  Poor boy was heartworm positive so he was treated by the rescue down South.  His poor teeth are so worn down, he may have lived his life outside on a chain chewing rocks. He was in such bad shape and suffered major hair loss.  After many medicated baths and a good diet his fur has grown in nicely.   He will need some work on his housebreaking as he was most likely kept outside all the time.  With structure, crate training and some patience this can be overcome.  He is a gentle soul.  He needs to learn how to walk on the leash, not sure if he ever has before.  JJ is a special boy who needs a kind, patient soul to spoil him after the rough life he has had.  If interested, please fill out an online application on our website

animal.description:
This sweet old soul is Moya. She is a 12 year old Husky mix who is currently available for adoption through Kenai Peninsula Animal Lovers (KPAL) Rescue. As a senior, she qualifies for our Senior and Special Needs (SAS) Pet Program - this means that her adoption fee can actually be credited towards the vet clinic of the adoptive familys choice. Read more about our SAS Pet Program down below! 

 

Before considering adding Moya to your family, please note that KPAL Rescue has a mandatory adoption process in place which includes a background check and a home visit. More information on our adoption process can be found in our pinned post, please read that (and this adoption post) in their entirety - our process cannot be waived. We do not ship our animals and we do not allow for third-party transportation.

 

This mature, polite lady has legs for days and is already potty-trained! Her dream home consists of family members that know how to be gentle and are spatially aware as she does have old hips and they can be sensitive to touch. She likes to be outside so a fenced yard or someone willing to walk her several times a day is ideal. She walks fairly well on a leash, but pulls a little if she sees something that peaks her interest. She is not fond of gunshots or fireworks. Her foster says she loves attention and isnt afraid to ask for it. She does have a little anxiety when left alone so somebody that can hang out at home with her or take her along is best. She loves car rides and will just lie down and rest her head on the center console, but does need a little extra help hopping in. Moya has previously had a negative encounter with a loose dog and this has led to her becoming very defensive around other dogs therefore shed be better as an only dog. She has not met cats. Moya would love to try the nearest doggy bed to you. 

 

KPAL Rescue dogs are fully vetted (vaccinated, microchipped, etc.) and spayed/neutered. Moya has no known health issues at this time but is classified as a senior so she qualifies for our Senior and Special Needs (SAS) Pet Program. This means that her adoption fee ($350) can be credited towards the veterinary clinic of the adoptive familys choice for any future medical expenses (medications, surgeries, end-of-life, etc.) for Moya. Serious inquires only, please, and feel free to share. 

 

If youre interested in adopting Moya, our adoption process is outlined in our pinned post and on our website: www.kpalrescue.org/pet-adoption/. Our Adoption Application can also be found on that website.

animal.description:
Doc is a five (5) year old, 75 pound lab whose owner was legally blind. He was not a seeing eye dog, but he was a constant companion for five years until further health issues required the owner to have to move to a care facility. The sister took Doc for a couple of weeks but he was not happy there and they were used to small dogs and did not want him, so they reached out and we agreed to take him. A few days later we had a foster and called to coordinate getting him and the sister had turned him into the shelter. This poor dog that was already depressed and confused now found himself in a scary shelter.

We have him now and he has been in a foster home but they have grandkids that come often and a very busy social life and Doc, who has literally lived cocooned with his owner, was overwhelmed and frightened. He is now in boarding and they are going to work with him to build his confidence and socialize him. When all is said and done, we think that Doc would be happiest in a quiet home with a companion or two. He is good in the house, crate trained and housetrained, very sweet and loves to play fetch. If you would like to have Doc for your best friend, please go to www.atlantalabrescue.com to fill out an application.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Friends! Are you ready for a Padfoot update?

Thanks to your generous Strut Your Mutt donations he had some extensive testing done last month. What we found out was that he has a couple of allergies (easily addressed) and he does NOT have Lupus. What he does have is called German Shepherd Pyoderma, also known as Deep Pyoderma.
This is a pretty uncommon disease, and it's taken a minute to figure it out. Basically, it's a lifelong skin issue that will have flare ups and will then get better with treatment, off and on for life. Treatment will include antibiotics, medicated baths and topical treatments. Not too scary!

So Padfoot is once again looking for his forever home!

This BIG, handsome guy is such a cool dog, he will make the BEST companion.
Padfoot is 3.5 years old and weighs in at 111lbs. He is good with other dogs and enjoys having doggy house mates, but he would also be fine as an only dog. Padfoot has a cute, fun personality and is affectionate and loving. He likes walks and car rides and squeaky toys. He is house trained, dog door trained and crate trained. He knows a few commands like sit and down and can catch a treat when thrown.
He is a *voracious* eater (he was basically starving when we got him!) and for that reason we are looking for a home with children over 8.
Padfoot is not a dog that needs work behaviorally or needs a ton of exercise. His main needs are a family to love him and care for him through his pyoderma flare ups.

If you are looking for a loving companion, a loyal friend to snuggle and hang out with you, Padfoot could be the best pal you're looking for. If you are the kind of person who can give him the ongoing care he will need, apply to meet Padfoot today at rescuerovers.org 2/2/21 1:34 PM

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.German Shepherd dogs, as well as the other herding breeds that we have in rescue, are highly active, energetic, working breeds. They require considerable vetting, exercise, socialization, training, leadership and mental stimuli in order to be well-adjusted, well-balanced, and well-mannered dogs. Even if you exercise and play with your dog daily in your fenced yard, you MUST still take your dog out on daily walks and outings in order to work on his/her leash skills, manners, and social skills. These breeds make great additions to active families who will pamper them, but who will also work with them, as they are smart dogs who need leadership, structure, plenty of activity and mental stimulation. If you are new to German Shepherds (and other herding breeds), please research the breed to make sure this is the dog for you. We ask that you consider the time and financial commitment that your German Shepherd (or other herding breed) dog will require before applying for one. Please review the section on our website (www.heartlandgsrescue.org) 'Is a HUGS Dog Right for You?' for additional information.This is how Peyton's awesome foster dad describes this sweet, shy boy: 'Peyton is a great dog that has improved a lot in the time that I've had him, and he is only going to keep getting better. He still has a lot to learn but he picks up things quickly, especially when treats are involved. He LOVES food! He responds well to his name. Peyton knows well 'sit', 'lay down', 'drop it', 'stay', 'leave it', and 'go to crate'. Peyton is working on his recall. By far his best trick is waiting patiently for meals until you say "ok". Peyton loves playing tug of war and fetch with his Kong toys and tennis balls, but his favorite is a knotted rope. I have not had luck with anything that squeaks since they only last about 15 minutes before he destroys them! When we're done playing, he likes to switch back and forth between spending time on my (his) bed or in his crate for naps. His favorite place in the house is his crate and where he feels safest. He's loves being petted but, in typical Shepherd fashion, on his terms. He is pretty independent and likes having alone time, but when it's time for bed, Peyton couldn't be cuddlier and likes to take up a minimum of 70 percent of my (his) bed.'
Sweet Peyton is cautious and introverted in new environments away from the people he knows. It will take extra time for him to adjust to his new home. Other than that, Peyton really enjoys people, whether they come to over to visit, or he sees them when he is out and about. Because of his large size (80lbs) and the fact that he has a tendency to try to greet everyone with puppyish enthusiasm, he will do best around adults (he is working on not jumping up in excitement). Peyton loves going for walks and car rides. He is great on car rides and enjoys going on them very much. He's very calm and just gazes out the car windows. Peyton used to be startled by traffic and loud noises on walks, but he is getting more used to those, and is doing better every day on walks! He loves walks in quiet areas, exploring trails, lakes, and sniffing new areas. Peyton is still a puppy at heart and knows how to use his size to his own advantage and can be a little stubborn at times (he will occasionally plant his butt down when he doesn't want to move). It just takes a little patience and persuation (or a good treat) to get him moving in the right direction! He would be great as an only dog. Peyton is currently the only dog in his foster home, but goes to doggy daycare on occasion and does well in small groups (he prefers laid-back dogs that do not get in his face). He also enjoys walks by himself and with doggy friends. Peyton has a sensitive stomach and is currently doing great eating Zignature Turkey kibble. Peyton is 80lbs and a tall build and he will need a handler that his fit, and steady on his/her feet, as he continues to learn good manners. Peyton's ideal adopter will have prior GSD experience and will continue his training -with positive reinforcement methods- (sit and wait, not jumping up, not mouthing, etc...). Payton will need a kind, patient adopter who understands he needs a little extra time to adjust, and who will allow him the personal space and time he needs to warm up on his own terms. He is a fabulous boy and a diamond in the rough, who will reward his lucky adopter with many years of happiness.Like all German Shepherds, Peyton would make a great addition to an active home that will provide the love, structure, good leadership, activity and mental stimulation that he needs. Because of that, Peyton's ideal owner will have prior GSD, or similar breed experience. Even if you exercise and play with your dog daily in your fenced yard, please remember that you MUST still take your dog out on daily walks and outings, in order to provide sufficient stimulation, ward off boredom, and work on leash skills, and manners. This boy is a diamond in the rough. He is going to make the right adopter very happy!
Peyton's adoption fee is $275 all of which goes back into offsetting our high-cost vetting expenses and rescuing more dogs. Adoption fees include spay/neuter, current on age-appropriate vaccinations, fecal, deworming, flea/tick and heartworm preventative, heartworm tested if old enough (treated if positive), and microchipped. Learn more about the adoption process and requirements, and apply at: http://heartlandgsrescue.rescuegroups.org/info/adoption., all of which goes back into offseting our high-cost vetting expenses and rescuing more dogs. Adoption fees include spay/neuter, current on age-appropriate vaccinations, fecal, deworming, flea/tick and heartworm preventative, heartworm tested if old enough (treated if positive), and microchipped. Learn more about the adoption process and requirements, and apply at: http://heartlandgsrescue.rescuegroups.org/info/adoption.Please review the information in the 'About Us', 'Important Considerations' and 'Adopt' sections on our website menu, as it contains useful information about the breed, adoption fees, the adoption process and our requirements, and how meeting the dogs works.

animal.description:
Please read Blairs story in full before submitting an application. You can also see videos and more pictures of her on our Facebook page, Rescue Row. Blair was welcomed into Rescue Row after we were contacted by a family who found their dog limp and bleeding. Blair had been attacked by another dog and shaken like a rag-doll.

We rushed her to the vet and x-rays showed that her spine was broken, which paralyzed her. After a couple weeks of healing, she began water therapy, walking in a wheelchair, and acupuncture in hopes of getting her up and walking again. Although she has made great progress, she still cannot fully walk 100% of the time. Surgery has been ruled out by a CT scan, but we are hoping with time she will end up being able to walk a little more each week. We are looking for an adopter who will continue working with her. We are unsure if she will ever walk again, but we are not giving up on her. She needs an adopter that either works from home or is home the majority of the time. Also an adopter that is able to carry her and lift her up on the couch and back down, she weighs 14 lbs. She loves going on car rides and her foster Mom tries to take her everywhere she can. She loves everyone she meets, but is very attached to her foster Mom so she will need an understanding adopter to allow her time to warm up in a new environment. No kids under the age of 14. She loves kids, but we do not want to take the chance that she could be dropped and re-injure her spine. Per Wisdom Panel she is 50% Chihuahua/12.5% Miniature Poodle/12.5% Yorkie/25% Mixed Breed groups. She is completely kennel trained, but needs to be carried outside and helped to go potty. She still does not have complete control of her bladder, so her adopter needs to be ok with accidents. Blair does not know she is different then the other dogs in the home and is such a happy and loving girl.

If you would like to adopt a dog from Rescue Row please fill out an application at https://form.jotform.com/91767055990166 

*Please check your junk email folder if you do not receive a response from a Rescue Row member within 48 hours.

*You must live within an hour of the DFW Metroplex because we do trial adoptions and require a homecheck

*Our adoption fees are as follows (paid by cash or a check made out to Rescue Row):

 Dogs 12 weeks-6 months old: $300 adoption fee

 Dogs 7 months and older: $275 adoption fee

Rescue Row is a 501(c)3 (non-profit) all volunteer dog rescue organization serving the DFW Metroplex. We are dedicated to rescuing dogs in shelters, dogs in abusive or neglectful situations, and dogs surrendered by their owners because of difficult circumstances. We place dogs in loving, responsible, committed permanent homes, following a comprehensive adoption process, which includes taking considerable care in finding good matches and educating prospective adopters about the responsibilities and costs of bringing a dog into their homes and lives. Dogs in our care are spayed or neutered, microchipped, receive all appropriate veterinary care and treatment, and placed in nurturing foster homes while they await placement in their permanent homes. We assist dogs in distress without regard to age, breed or ease of placement. Dogs in the greatest need take priority. Finally, we strive to work with shelters and other rescue and humane organizations to develop a network of supporters and volunteers in order to create a better world for homeless dogs.
